tsoratorium / Christmas Oratorio\n| website = [[Carus-Verlag]]\n| year = 2005\n| page = V\n| accessdate = 15 November 2013\n| ref = harv\n}}-->\n* {{cite web\n| last = Rathey\n| first = Markus\n| url = https://ism.yale.edu/sites/default/files/files/Johann%20Sebastian%20Bach.pdf\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach's Mass in B Minor: The Greatest Artwork of All Times and All People\n| website = ism.yale.edu\n| date = 18 April 2003\n| accessdate = 14 November 2013\n| ref = {{sfnref|Rathey|2003}}\n}}\n<!--\n* {{cite web\n| last = Sch\u00f6newolf\n| first = Markus\n| url = https://schoenewolf.com/bach-weihnachtsoratorium/\n| title = J. S. Bach, Weihnachtsoratorium: Werkeinf\u00fchrung und Libretto\n| website = schoenewolf.com\n| date = 2019\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 15 November 2013\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| url = https://www.konzerthaus-dortmund.de/page/MediaLib/file/Programmheft/200809/Programm-Weihnachtsoratorium.pdf\n| title = Ah! Lord, how shall I meet Thee\n| website = [[Konzerthaus Dortmund]]\n| date = 6 December 2008\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 15 November 2018\n| ref = {{sfnref|Konzerthaus Dortmund|2008}}\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| url = https://hymnary.org/text/o_lord_how_shall_i_meet_thee\n| title = Ah! Lord, how shall I meet Thee\n| website = hymnary.org\n| accessdate = 16 December 2017\n| ref = {{sfnref|Hymnary|2019}}\n}}-->\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Christmas Oratorio}}\n* {{IMSLP|work=Weihnachtsoratorium, BWV 248 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|cname=Weihnachtsoratorium, BWV 248}}\n* Markus Sch\u00f6newolf: [https://schoenewolf.com/bach-weihnachtsoratorium/ Weihnachtsoratorium] schoenewolf.com\n* [http://www.bachdiskographie.de/textkangeist/bwv248_IItext.html BWV 248 / II] bachdiskographie.de\n<!--\n* {{IMSLP|work=T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten!, BWV 214 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|cname=T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten!, BWV 214}}\n* {{cite web\n| last = Mincham\n| first = Julian\n| url = http://www.jsbachcantatas.com/documents/chapter-95-bwv-214.htm\n| title = Chapter 95 BWV 214 T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten! / Resound Drums, ring out Trumpets!\n| publisher = jsbachcantatas\n| accessdate = 7 June 2013\n}}-->\n\n{{Masses, Magnificat, Passions and Oratorios by Johann Sebastian Bach}}\n{{Church cantatas by Johann Sebastian Bach}}\n{{Bach cantatas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend'', BWV 248 II}}\n\n[[Category:Church cantatas by Johann Sebastian Bach]]\n[[Category:1734 compositions]]\n[[Category:Christmas cantatas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical composition\n| title         = {{lang|de|Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend}}\n| subtitle      = Part II of ''[[Christmas Oratorio]]''\n| composer      = [[Johann Sebastian Bach|J. S. Bach]]\n| type          = [[Christmas cantata]]\n| image         = BWV248-II-sinfonia-1.jpg\n| image_alt     = \n| image_upright = 1.3\n| caption       = [[Autograph (manuscript)|Autograph]] of the beginning of the Sinfonia\n| catalogue     = [[BWV]] 248 II\n| related       = <!--based on {{hlist| [[T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten!|BWV 214]] | [[La\u00dft uns sorgen, la\u00dft uns wachen, BWV 213|BWV 213]] }}-->\n| performed     = {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1734|12|26|df=y}}|location=[[Leipzig]]}}\n| movements     = 14\n| text          = {{plainlist|\n* {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Luke|chapter=2|verse=8|range=\u201314}}<!--\n* from \"[[Vom Himmel hoch, da komm ich her]]\"-->\n}}\n| vocal         = [[SATB|{{abbr|SATB|soprano, alto, tenor and bass}}]] choir and soloists\n| instrumental  = {{hlist | 2&nbsp;[[traverso]]s | 2&nbsp;[[oboe]]s | 2&nbsp;[[oboe d'amore|oboes d'amore]] | 2&nbsp;[[oboe da caccia|oboes da caccia]] | 2&nbsp;[[violin]]s | [[viola]] | [[cello]] | [[violone]] | [[basso continuo|continuo]] }}\n| italic_title  = no\n}}\n'''{{lang|de|Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend}}''' (\"And there were shepherds in the same environs\"),{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA118 118]}} [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis|BWV]]&nbsp;248<sup>II</sup> (also written as '''BWV&nbsp;248&nbsp;II'''),{{sfn|Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend (Christmas oratorio, part 2) BWV 248 II at Bach Digital}} is a 1734 [[Christmas cantata]] by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] as the second part of his ''[[Christmas Oratorio]]''. Bach was then ''[[Thomaskantor]]'', responsible for music at four churches in [[Leipzig]], a position he had assumed in 1723.\n\nThe cantata follows the [[nativity of Jesus]] as narrated in the [[Gospel of Luke]]. It covers the [[annunciation to the shepherds]]. An unknown librettist added text for reflecting [[recitative]]s and [[aria]]s and included stanzas from [[Lutheran hymn]]s. Bach structured the cantata in 14 movements and scored it for four vocal parts and a [[Baroque instruments|Baroque orchestra]] with flutes, oboes and strings. He led the first performances at the two main churches of Leipzig on 26 December 1734 during morning and [[vespers]] services.\n\nPart II of the oratorio begins, in contrast to the other parts, with the instrumental [[Sinfonia]], a concerto of shepherds and angels. A [[tenor]] soloist narrates the Biblical story in recitative as the [[Evangelist (Bach)|Evangelist]]. The [[soprano]] soloist makes a first appearance in the oratorio as the [[angel]], and is followed by the choir representing the angels singing \"[[Glory to God in the Highest]]\". There are three chorales, one by [[Johann Rist]] and two by [[Paul Gerhardt]], both using the melody of Luther's \"[[Vom Himmel hoch, da komm ich her]]\".\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|Church cantata#Second Day of Christmas}}\nIn 18th-century [[Leipzig]], high holidays were celebrated on three consecutive days, with different prescribed readings and related music each day. [[Christmas]], one of these high holidays, was celebrated from 25 to 27&nbsp;December. For the principal churches, [[Thomaskirche]] and [[Nikolaikirche, Leipzig|Nikolaikirche]], the [[Thomaskantor|director musices]] determined which music was to be performed during the services on Sundays and feast days.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|pp=23\u201326}}{{sfn|Buelow|2016|p=272}}{{sfn|Wolff|2002|pp=253\u2013254}}\n\nOn the Second Day of Christmas, 26&nbsp;December, Leipzig celebrated Christmas in even years and [[St.&nbsp;Stephen's Day]] in uneven years, with different readings. For even years, the epistle for Christmas was {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Titus|chapter=3|verse=4|range=\u20137}} and the gospel was {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Luke|chapter=2|verse=15|range=\u201320}}. The theme of the first  reading is God's mercy appearing in Christ and that of the second the [[Adoration of the Shepherds|shepherds at the manger]].{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA106 106]}}\n\n===Bach in Leipzig===\n{{see also|Church cantata (Bach)#Second Day of Christmas|Secular cantata (Bach)#Music celebrating the Saxonian prince-electoral family}}\n[[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]] had become director musices in Leipzig in 1723.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|pp=23\u201326}} Early in his tenure, he had composed these [[church cantata]]s for the Second Day of Christmas, which was held as [[Saint Stephen's Day|St.&nbsp;Stephen's Day]] in uneven years:\n* 1723: [[Darzu ist erschienen der Sohn Gottes, BWV 40|''Darzu ist erschienen der Sohn Gottes'', BWV&nbsp;40]], part of [[Bach's first cantata cycle]]{{sfn|Darzu ist erschienen der Sohn Gottes BWV 40: Sacred cantata (2nd Christmas Day) at Bach Digital}}\n* 1724: [[Christum wir sollen loben schon, BWV 121|''Christum wir sollen loben schon'', BWV&nbsp;121]], part of the [[chorale cantata cycle]]{{sfn|Christum wir sollen loben schon BWV 121: Chorale cantata (2nd Christmas Day) at Bach Digital}}\n* 1725: [[Selig ist der Mann, BWV 57|''Selig ist der Mann'', BWV&nbsp;57]], part of [[Bach's third cantata cycle]]{{sfn|Selig ist der Mann, der die Anfechtung erduldet (Dialogus) BWV 57: Sacred cantata (2nd Christmas Day) at Bach Digital}}\n[[File:Maria Josepha von Sachsen-Litauen-Polen-\u00d6sterreich.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=bust painting of a young festively dressed woman, whose body is turned to the right but who is facing the viewer, |[[Maria Josepha of Austria|Maria Josepha]], the dedicatee of BWV&nbsp;214, in a 1720 painting by {{nowrap|[[Rosalba Carriera]]}}]]\nIn 1733, [[Augustus III of Poland]] succeeded his father, [[Augustus II of Poland|Augustus the Strong]], as Elector of Saxony and took residence in [[Dresden]].{{sfn|Rathey|2003}} Bach hoped to become court composer for the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] Elector, and dedicated a Latin Missa to him that year, the [[Mass for the Dresden court (Bach)|Kyrie\u2013Gloria Mass in B&nbsp;minor, BWV&nbsp;232&nbsp;I]].{{sfn|Rathey|2003}} Several of [[List of secular cantatas by Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach's secular cantatas]] celebrating the Saxonian prince-electoral family were performed in Leipzig, including these two cantatas first performed in 1733:{{sfn|Wessel|2015|pp=25\u201344, 47, 99\u2013100}}\n* [[La\u00dft uns sorgen, la\u00dft uns wachen, BWV 213|''La\u00dft uns sorgen, la\u00dft uns wachen'', BWV&nbsp;213]], also known as {{lang|de|Hercules am Scheidewege}} (''Hercules at the Crossroads''), on a libretto by [[Picander]], was performed on {{nowrap|5 September 1733}}, the 11th birthday of the son of the elector;{{sfn|Wessel|2015|pp=25\u201344, 47, 99\u2013100}}{{sfn|Lasst uns sorgen, lasst uns wachen (Dramma per musica) BWV 213: Secular cantata at Bach Digital}}\n* A cantata for the elector's wife, [[Maria Josepha of Austria|Maria Josepha]], to honour her 34th birthday on 8 December:{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA102 102],820,827\u2013830}} {{lang|de|[[T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten! BWV 214|''T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten!'' BWV 214]]|italic=unset}} (''Resound, ye drums! Ring out, ye trumpets!'').{{sfn|T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten! BWV 214: Secular cantata (Birthday) at Bach Digital}} It is also known as \"{{lang|de|Gl\u00fcckwunschkantate zum Geburtstage der K\u00f6nigin}}\" (''Congratulation cantata for the Queen's birthday''), although Maria Josepha was not crowned Queen of Poland until January 1734.{{sfn|Wessel|2015|pp=25\u201344, 47, 99\u2013100}}\n\n===Christmas season 1734\u201335===\n{{See also|Christmas Oratorio}}\nBach composed [[Christmas Oratorio|his ''Christmas Oratorio'']] for the [[Christmastide|Christmas season]] from Christmas Day on 25&nbsp;December 1734 to [[Epiphany (holiday)|Epiphany]] on 6&nbsp;January 1735.{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=V}} {{lang|de|Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend}}, {{nowrap|BWV 248 II}}, for the Second Day of Christmas in 1734, is the second of six cantatas (or parts) constituting this oratorio. Its first cantata, [[Jauchzet, frohlocket! Auf, preiset die Tage, BWV 248 I|''Jauchzet, frohlocket! Auf, preiset die Tage'', BWV&nbsp;248&nbsp;I]], had been performed the previous day.{{sfn|Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend (Christmas oratorio, part 2) BWV 248 II at Bach Digital}}\n[[File:Govert Flinck - Angels Announcing the Birth of Christ to the Shepherds - WGA07928.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|''Angels Announcing the Birth of Christ to the Shepherds'' by [[Govert Flinck]], 1639]]\nWhile Part&nbsp;I of the oratorio covers the birth of Jesus, Part&nbsp;II is focused on the [[annunciation to the shepherds]].{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA120 120]}} The story is told following the Gospel of Luke, interspersed with reflecting [[recitative]]s, [[aria]]s and [[chorale]]s.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA118 118]}} Deviating from the prescribed reading, the text of the cantata covers exclusively the announcement,{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA119 119]}} while the itinerary to Bethlehem and adoration are topics of Part III, [[Herrscher des Himmels, erh\u00f6re das Lallen, BWV 248 III|''Herrscher des Himmels, erh\u00f6re das Lallen'', BWV&nbsp;248&nbsp;III]], first performed on the Third Day of Christmas, 27&nbsp;December 1734.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA131 131\u2013133]}}\n[[File:BWV 248 Libretto.JPG|thumb|upright=1.3|First two pages of the libretto of Bach's ''Christmas Oratorio'', as printed in 1734{{sfn|D-LEm I. B. 2a at Bach Digital}}]]\nThe identity of the [[Libretto|librettist]] of the ''Christmas Oratorio'' cantatas is unknown,{{sfn|Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend (Christmas oratorio, part 2) BWV 248 II at Bach Digital}} with [[Picander]], who had collaborated with Bach earlier, a likely candidate.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA104 104]}} The oratorio's libretto was published in 1734.{{sfn|D-LEm I. B. 2a at Bach Digital}} The [[dictum (music)|quotations from the Bible]] are rendered in [[Martin Luther]]'s translation. The librettist included three stanzas from [[Lutheran hymn]]s: [[Johann Rist]]'s \"Brich an, o sch\u00f6nes Morgenlicht\" from \"[[Ermuntre dich, mein schwacher Geist]]\",{{sfn|Dahn 12|2019}} [[Paul Gerhardt]]'s \"Schaut hin! dort liegt im finstern Stall\" from \"[[Schaut, schaut, was ist f\u00fcr Wunder dar]]\",{{sfn|Dahn 17|2019}} as the central movement of the cantata, and for the conclusion, by the same author, \"Wir singen dir in deinem Heer\" from \"[[Wir singen dir, Immanuel]]\".{{sfn|Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend (Christmas oratorio, part 2) BWV 248 II at Bach Digital}}{{sfn|Dahn 23|2019}}{{sfn|Dellal|2019}}\n\nThe three movements based on Lutheran hymn text used [[Lutheran chorale]] tunes associated with these hymns:{{sfn|Dahn 12|2019}}{{sfn|Dahn 17|2019}}{{sfn|Dahn 23|2019}}\n* \"Ermuntre dich, mein schwacher Geist\", [[Zahn number|Zahn]]&nbsp;5741b, by [[Johann Schop]] (1641), for the first chorale movement{{sfn|Ermuntre dich, mein schwacher Geist BWV 248/12 at Bach Digital}}{{sfn|Zahn|1889\u20131893|loc=III, pp.&nbsp;[https://archive.org/details/1508285990bsb11304501/page/n521/mode/2up 516\u2013517]}}\n* \"[[Vom Himmel hoch da komm ich her]]\", Zahn&nbsp;345\u2013346, by Martin Luther (1539), for the second and third chorale movements{{sfn|Vom Himmel hoch, da komm ich her BWV 248/17 at Bach Digital}}{{sfn|Vom Himmel hoch da komm ich her BWV 248/23 at Bach Digital}}{{sfn|Zahn|1889\u20131893|loc=I, p.&nbsp;[https://archive.org/details/1508283124bsb11304498/page/n105/mode/2up 98]}}\n\nTwo extended movements of {{nowrap|BWV 248 II}} are based on music from the BWV&nbsp;213 and 214 cantatas:{{sfn|Wessel|2015|p=47}}\n* the sixth movement of {{nowrap|BWV 248 II}}, \"Frohe Hirten, eilt, ach eilet\", is based on the aria \"Fromme Musen! meine Glieder\" from BWV&nbsp;214;{{sfn|Wessel|2015|p=47}}\n* the tenth movement of the cantata for the Second Day of Christmas 1734, \"Schlafe, mein Liebster, genie\u00dfe der Ruh'\", is based on the aria \"Schlafe, mein Liebster, und pflege der Ruh\" from BWV&nbsp;213.{{sfn|Wessel|2015|p=47}}\n\n{{nowrap|BWV 248 II}} was first performed in the Thomaskirche on 26 December 1734 and repeated during a [[vespers]] service at the Nikolaikirche the same day.{{sfn|Wolff|2002|p=254}}\n\n== Music ==\n=== Structure and scoring ===\nThe work is structured in 14 [[Movement (music)|movement]]s. Bach scored it for four vocal soloists, a [[SATB|four-part choir]] ([[SATB|{{abbr|SATB|soprano, alto, tenor and bass}}]]) and a [[Baroque instruments|Baroque instrumental]] ensemble of two [[traverso]]s (Tra), two [[Oboe d'amore|oboes d'amore]] (Oa), two [[Oboe da caccia|oboes da caccia]] (Oc), two [[violin]]s (Vl), [[viola]] (Va) and [[basso continuo]].{{sfn|Bischof|2019}} The wind instruments illustrate the sphere of the shepherds. A typical performance takes 29 minutes.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA118 118]}}\n\nThe cantata begins with the instrumental [[Sinfonia]], unlike all other parts of the oratorio. The [[tenor]] soloist narrates the story as the [[Evangelist (Bach)|Evangelist]]. The soprano soloist appears for the first time in the oratorio as the angel bringing the news. The choir represents the angels singing \"Ehre sei Gott in der H\u00f6he\" (Glory to God in the Highest). The scene is reflected in two arias, an alto aria anticipating a [[lullaby]] for the newborn and a tenor aria calling to run to the manger in joy.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA118 118\u2013120]}}\n\nThe following table follows the {{lang|de|[[Neue Bach-Ausgabe]]}} (''New Bach Edition''). The numbers are continuous for the complete ''Christmas Oratorio'', beginning with 10 for its second cantata. The [[Key (music)|keys]] and [[time signature]]s are from [[Alfred D\u00fcrr]] and use the symbol for common time.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA118 118\u2013120]}} The continuo, played throughout, is not shown.\n\n{{Classical movement header | show_text_source = yes | work = {{lang|de|Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend}} | instruments1 = Winds | instruments2 = Strings }}\n\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#10|10]]\n| title = {{lang|it|Sinfonia|italic=no}}\n| text_source = \n| type = \n| vocal = \n| instruments1 = 2Tra 2Oa 2Oc\n| instruments2 = 2Vl Va\n| key = [[G major]]\n| time = [[Compound meter (music)|12/8]]\n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#11|11]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend|italic=no}}\n| text_source = {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Luke|chapter=2|verse=8|range=\u20139}}\n| type = Recitative\n| vocal = T\n| instruments1 = \n| instruments2 = \n| key = \n| time = \n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#12|12]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Brich an, o sch\u00f6nes Morgenlicht|italic=no}}\n| text_source = Rist\n| type = Chorale\n| vocal = SATB\n| instruments1 = 2Tra 2Oa 2Oc\n| instruments2 = 2Vl Va\n| key = G major\n| time = {{music|common-time}}\n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#13|13]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Und der Engel sprach zu ihnen<br />F\u00fcrchtet euch nicht|italic=no}}\n| text_source = {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Luke|chapter=2|verse=10|range=-11}}\n| type = Recitative\n| vocal = T<br> S\n| instruments1 = \n| instruments2 = <br />2Vl Va\n| key = \n| time = \n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#14|14]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Was Gott dem Abraham verhei\u00dfen|italic=no}}\n| text_source = anon.\n| type = Recitative\n| vocal = B\n| instruments1 = 2Oa 2Oc\n| instruments2 = 2Vl Va\n| key = \n| time = \n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#15|15]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Frohe Hirten, eilt, ach eilet|italic=no}}\n| text_source = anon.\n| type = Aria\n| vocal = T\n| instruments1 = 2Oa 2Oc\n| instruments2 = 2Vl Va\n| key = [[E minor]]\n| time = 3/8\n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#16|16]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Und das habt zum Zeichen|italic=no}}\n| text_source = {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Luke|chapter=2|verse=12}}\n| type = Recitative\n| vocal = T{{efn|In some{{which|date=December 2019}} performances sung by the soprano (Angel){{citation needed|date=December 2019}}}}\n| instruments1 = \n| instruments2 = \n| key = \n| time = \n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#17|17]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Schaut hin! dort liegt im finstern Stall|italic=no}}\n| text_source = Gerhardt\n| type = Chorale\n| vocal = SATB\n| instruments1 = 2Tra 2Oa 2Oc\n| instruments2 = 2Vl Va\n| key = [[C major]]\n| time = {{music|common-time}}\n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#18|18]]\n| title = {{lang|de|So geht denn hin!|italic=no}}\n| text_source = anon.\n| type = Recitative\n| vocal = B\n| instruments1 = 2Ob 2Oc\n| instruments23 = 2Vl Va\n| key = \n| time = \n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#19|19]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Schlafe, mein Liebster, genie\u00dfe der Ruh|italic=no}}\n| text_source = anon.\n| type = Aria\n| vocal = A\n| instruments1 = Tra 2Oa 2Oc\n| instruments2 = 2Vl Va\n| key = [[G Major]]\n| time = 2/4\n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#20|20]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Und alsobald war da bei dem Engel|italic=no}}\n| text_source = {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Luke|chapter=2|verse=13}}\n| type = Recitative\n| vocal = T\n| instruments1 = \n| instruments2 = \n| key = \n| time = \n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#21|21]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Ehre sei Gott in der H\u00f6he|italic=no}}\n| text_source = {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Luke|chapter=2|verse=14}}\n| type = Chorus\n| vocal = SATB\n| instruments1 = 2Tra 2Oa 2Oc\n| instruments2 = \n| key = G major\n| time = {{music|alla-breve}}\n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#22|22]]\n| title = {{lang|de|So recht, ihr Engel, jauchzt und singet|italic=no}}\n| text_source = anon.\n| type = Recitative\n| vocal = B\n| instruments1 = \n| instruments2 = \n| key = \n| time = \n}}\n{{Classical movement row\n| number = [[#23|23]]\n| title = {{lang|de|Wir singen dir in deinem Heer|italic=no}}\n| text_source = Gerhardt\n| type = Chorale\n| vocal = SATB\n| instruments1 = 2Tra 2Oa 2Oc \n| instruments2 = 2Vl Va \n| key = G major\n| time = 12/8\n}}\n\n{{End}}\n\n=== Movements ===\n==== 10 ====\n[[File:BWV248-II-sinfonia-2.jpg|thumb|Second page of Sinfonia]]\nThe cantata begins with the instrumental [[Sinfonia]].{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA118 118]}}{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=34}} Set in G major, it is in a triple meter in [[siciliano]] rhythm. [[Albert Schweitzer]] likened the music to a concerto of the shepherds, playing oboes, and the angels playing strings and flute in unison with the first violin. The movement is a ternary form, ABA', repeating the beginning modified after a middle section, and this a forerunner of the classical [[sonata form]], as D\u00fcrr notes.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA120 120]}} Each section is in again three groups, taking the analogy to the sonata form further: string music, as a first theme, is followed by oboe music as a second theme and combined music as the closing group.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA120 120]}} The movement is the only purely instrumental music in the ''Christmas Oratorio''.{{sfn|Bossuyt|2004|p=87}}\n\nThe absence of a chorus in the first movement signifies the stillness of the nightly scene, giving more weight to the voices to follow. The major choral movement in this cantata is the representation of the angels' song.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA120 120]}}\n\n==== 11 ====\nThe [[tenor]] soloist as the [[Evangelist (Bach)|Evangelist]] begins the narration in [[secco recitative]] after Luke: {{lang|de|\"Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend\"|italic=no}} (\"And there were shepherds in the same region\"),{{sfn|Dellal|2019}} describing the shepherds in the fields, frightened by the apparition of angels.{{sfn|Dellal|2019}}{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=37}}\n\n==== 12 ====\nIn the response to the shepherds being afraid, they are told in a chorale not to fear.{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=38}} The stanza \"Brich an, o sch\u00f6nes Morgenlicht\" {{sfn|Dahn 12|2019}} (\"Break forth, o lovely light of morning\"),{{sfn|Dellal|2019}} which Bach set for four parts, is taken from a hymn by Johann Rist, \"Ermuntre dich, mein schwacher Geist\":{{sfn|Dahn 12|2019}}\n\n{{quote|<poem>Brich an, o sch\u00f6nes Morgenlicht,\nUnd la\u00df den Himmel tagen!\nDu Hirtenvolk, erschrecke nicht,\nWeil dir die Engel sagen,\nDa\u00df dieses schwache Kn\u00e4belein\nSoll unser Trost und Freude sein,\nDazu den Satan zwingen\nUnd letztlich Friede bringen!</poem>}}\n\nThe shepherds are told that the weak child shall be comfort and joy to them and all (using the first person plural) and will conquer [[Satan]] and ultimately bring peace.{{sfn|Dellal|2019}} Markus Rathey notes that this is an apocalyptic outlook within the oratorio.{{sfn|Rathey|2016|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=UHDADAAAQBAJ&pg=PA60 60]}}\n\n==== 13 ====\nThe narration continues, first sung by the Evangelist, \"{{lang|de|Und der Engel sprach zu ihnen|italic=no}}\" (\"And the angel said to them\"),{{sfn|Dellal|2019}} then continued by the angel's message, given to the soprano soloist, who appears here for the first time in the oratorio: \"{{lang|de|F\u00fcrchtet euch nicht|italic=no}}\" (\"Do not be afraid\").{{sfn|Dellal|2019}} The angel's recitative is accompanied by strings.{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=39}}\n\n==== 14 ====\nThe announcement of the angel is interrupted after telling of the birth of the Saviour, by a recitative and following aria. The bass sings the recitative, accompanied by the oboes representing the shepherds: \"{{lang|de|Was Gott dem Abraham verhei\u00dfen|italic=no}}\" (\"What God promised to Abraham\").{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA119 119]}} It connects the message to the shepherds to [[Abraham]], who also was a shepherd.{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=39}}\n\n==== 15 ====\nThe tenor sings an aria, calling the other shepherds to run to see the child: \"{{lang|de|Frohe Hirten, eilt, ach eilet|italic=no}}\" (\"Joyful shepherds, hurry, oh hurry\").{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA119 119]}} The aria in E minor is accompanied by all oboes and strings.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA119 119]}}{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=40}} The music is based on the aria \"Fromme Musen, meine Glieder\" from Bach's secular cantata [[T\u00f6net, ihr  Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten! BWV 214|''T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten!'', BWV 214]], for the birthday of [[Maria Josepha of Austria|Maria Josepha]], Electress of Saxony.{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=V}}\n\n==== 16 ====\nThe announcement of the angel is continued: \"{{lang|de|Und das habt zum Zeichen|italic=no}}\" (\"And this shall be a sign for you\"),{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA119 119]}} mentioning swaddling-clothes and the manger.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA119 119]}} The movement is marked to be sung by the tenor,{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=44}} which shows, according to D\u00fcrr, the \"essentially undramatic conception of the oratorio\".{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA120 120]}} Some{{which|date=December 2019}} performances let the soprano, the angel's voice, continue.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n==== 17 ====\nAt this point, the lowliness of the humble stable is reflected in a [[chorale]]:{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=45}} \"{{lang|de|Schaut hin! dort liegt im finstern Stall|italic=no}}\" (Look, there lies in a dark stable),{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA119 119]}} a setting for four parts of a stanza by Paul Gerhardt, which is sung to the melody of Martin Luther's \"[[Vom Himmel hoch, da komm ich her]]\".{{sfn|Dahn 17|2019}} This chorale, in the low key of C major, is the central movement of this cantata and thus also the midpoint of the first three parts of the oratorio, performed on the three days of Christmas:{{sfn|Rathey|2016|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=UHDADAAAQBAJ&pg=PA216 216]}}\n\n{{quote|<poem>Schaut hin, dort liegt im finstern Stall,\nDes Herrschaft gehet \u00fcberall!\nDa Speise vormals sucht ein Rind,\nDa ruhet itzt der Jungfrau'n Kind.</poem>}}\n\nIts focus is on the dark stable, expressing amazement that the Almighty, the Virgin's child, rests where a cow had fed.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA121 121]}} Bach illustrates power over all by a rising scale of more than an octave in the bass line.{{sfn|Rathey|2016|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=UHDADAAAQBAJ&pg=PA216 216]}}\n\n==== 18 ====\nAnother reflecting recitative of the bass, again interrupting the Biblical account, calls the shepherds to go and marvel: \"{{lang|de|So geht denn hin, ihr Hirten, geht|italic=no}}\" (\"Then go forth, you shepherds, go\"),.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA119 119]}} It is accompanied by the oboes as the first bass recitative.{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=46}}\n\n==== 19 ====\nThe aria is assigned to the alto voice.{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=46}} It is a lullaby, as if imagined: \"{{lang|de|Schlafe, mein Liebster, genie\u00dfe der Ruh|italic=no}}\" (\"Sleep, my most beloved, enjoy your rest\").{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA119 119\u2013120]}} Set in G major, the voice is doubled by a flute playing an [[octave]] higher, and all oboes and strings.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA121 121]}} Bach based the music on \"{{lang|de|Schlafe, mein Liebster}}\", a soprano aria from ''La\u00dft uns sorgen, la\u00dft uns wachen'', BWV 213.{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=V}}\n\n==== 20 ====\nThe Evangelist continues the narration:{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=52}} \"{{lang|de|Und alsobald war da bei dem Engel|italic=no}}\" (\"And suddenly there was with the angel\"),{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA120 120]}} telling of the heavenly hosts.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA120 120]}}\n\n==== 21 ====\nThe choir represents the angels singing the words after Luke:{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=53}} \"{{lang|de|Ehre sei Gott in der H\u00f6he und Friede auf Erden und den Menschen ein Wohlgefallen.|italic=no}}\" (\"Glory to God on high and peace on Earth and goodwill towards mankind.\").{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA120 120]}} Bach treats the three aspects differently, as in a [[motet]]. The instruments only accompany. The first section, about glory, is developed in dense [[polyphony]] based on a [[passacaglia]]-type bass. The second section, about peace, is set to a [[pedal point]].{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=55}} The third section, about goodwill, has lively [[Theme (music)|theme]]s full of [[coloratura]]s.{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=55}} After each idea has received extended treatment, the full text is repeated in the same sequence but condensed.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA121 121]}}\n\n==== 22 ====\nThe bass sings a third recitative, this time secco:{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=59}} \"{{lang|de|So recht, ihr Engel, jauchzt uns singet|italic=no}}\" (\"Quite right, you angels, rejoice and sing\"), calling to joyfully join the angels' song.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA120 120]}}\n\n==== 23 ====\nThe closing chorale{{sfn|Hofmann|2005|p=59}} is another stanza by Gerhardt, to the same melody as the cantata's central chorale: \"{{lang|de|Wir singen dir in deinem Heer|italic=no}}\"{{sfn|Dahn 23|2019}} (\"We sing to You within Your host\"):{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA120 120]}}\n\n{{quote|<poem>Wir singen dir in deinem Heer\nAus aller Kraft Lob, Preis und Ehr,\nDa\u00df du, o lang gew\u00fcnschter Gast,\nDich nunmehr eingestellet hast.</poem>}}\n\nUsing the first person plural, it includes everyone in singing praises with the angels because the long-awaited guest has finally appeared.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA120 120]}} The chorale is set in G major, and instrumental motifs between the lines are taken from the opening Sinfonia, confirming the symmetry of the cantata's structure.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Jones|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA121 121]}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist | 20em}}\n\n== Cited sources ==\n''[[Bach Digital]]''\n* {{BDh|148|00|2019-03-11|Work|Christum wir sollen loben schon BWV 121: Chorale cantata (2nd Christmas Day)}}\n* {{BDh|55|000|2019-03-11|Work|Darzu ist erschienen der Sohn Gottes BWV 40: Sacred cantata (2nd Christmas Day)}}\n* {{BDh|25367||2018-09-08|Source|D-LEm I. B. 2a}}\n* {{BDh|11260||2018-07-15|Work|Ermuntre dich, mein schwacher Geist BWV 248/12}}\n* {{BDh|269|00|2019-03-11|Work|Lasst uns sorgen, lasst uns wachen (Dramma per musica) BWV 213: Secular cantata}}\n* {{BDh|72|000|2019-03-11|Work|Selig ist der Mann, der die Anfechtung erduldet (Dialogus) BWV 57: Sacred cantata (2nd Christmas Day)}}\n* {{BDh|270|00|2019-03-11|Work|T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten! BWV 214: Secular cantata (Birthday)}}\n* {{BDh|11386||2019-03-11|Work|Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend (Christmas oratorio, part 2) BWV 248 II}}\n* {{BDh|11261||2019-01-18|Work|Vom Himmel hoch, da komm ich her BWV 248/17}}\n* {{BDh|11281||2019-01-17|Work|Vom Himmel hoch da komm ich her BWV 248/23}}\n\n''Books''\n* {{cite book\n| last = Buelow\n| first = George J.\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=1uuuCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA272\n| title = The Late Baroque Era\n| work = The Late Baroque Era: Vol 4. From The 1680s To 1740\n| publisher = [[Springer Publishing|Springer]]\n| year = 2016\n| isbn = 978-9-05-867421-0\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Bossuyt\n| first = Ignace\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Uba5l4K5KvAC&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach, Christmas Oratorio (BWV 248)\n| publisher = [[Leuven University Press]]\n| year = 2004\n| isbn = 978-1-34-911303-3\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = D\u00fcrr\n| first = Alfred\n| authorlink = Alfred D\u00fcrr\n| last2 = Jones\n| first2 = Richard D. P.\n| author2link = Richard D. P. Jones\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=m9JuwslMcq4C&pg=PA118\n| title = The Cantatas of J. S. Bach: With Their Librettos in German-English Parallel Text\n| publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]\n| year = 2006\n| isbn = 978-0-19-929776-4\n| pages = 118\u2013121\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| translator-last1 = Coombs\n| translator-first1 = John\n| date = 2005\n| editor-last = Hofmann\n| editor-first = Klaus\n| editor-link = Klaus Hofmann\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach: Weihnachtsoratorium / Christmas Oratorio / Oratorium Tempore Nativitatis Christi / BWV 248\n| url = https://www.carusmedia.com/images-intern/medien/30/3124853/3124853x.pdf\n| type = [[Urtext edition|Urtext]], Vocal score\n| series = Stuttgarter Bach-Ausgaben\n| language = de, en, fr\n| others = Continuo realisation by Horn, Paul, English version by Drinker, Henry S.\n| publisher = [[Carus Verlag|Carus]]\n| id = CV 31.248/53\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Rathey\n| first = Markus\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=UHDADAAAQBAJ&pg=PA148\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach's Christmas Oratorio: Music, Theology, Culture\n| publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]\n| date = 2016\n| isbn = 978-0-19-027526-6\n| pages = 148\u2013152\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Wessel\n| first = Jens\n| chapter-url = https://ediss.sub.uni-hamburg.de//volltexte/2016/7928/pdf/Dissertation.pdf\n| chapter = K\u00f6then (1717\u20131723)\n| title = J. S. Bach und die italienische Oper / Drammi per musica f\u00fcr das kurf\u00fcrstlich-s\u00e4chsische und polnische K\u00f6nigshaus zwischen 1733 und 1736\n| publisher = [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik und Theater Hamburg]]\n| date = 2015\n| pages = 25\u201344, 47, 99\u2013100\n| language = German\n| type = dissertation\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Wolff\n| first = Christoph\n| authorlink = Christoph Wolff\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=NHpL3cQg0_UC&pg=PA237\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach: The Learned Musician\n| publisher = [[W. W. Norton & Company]]\n| year = 2002\n| isbn = 978-0-393-32256-9\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last1       = Zahn\n  | first1      = Johannes\n  | author-link1= Johannes Zahn\n  | date        = 1889\u20131893\n  | title       = [[scores:Die Melodien der deutschen evangelischen Kirchenlieder (Zahn, Johannes)|Die Melodien der deutschen evangelischen Kirchenlieder]]\n  | volume      = [https://archive.org/details/1508283124bsb11304498 I] \u2013 [https://archive.org/details/1508284209bsb11304500 II] \u2013 [https://archive.org/details/1508285990bsb11304501 III] \u2013 [https://archive.org/details/1508286757bsb11304502 IV] \u2013 [https://archive.org/details/1508287113bsb11304503 V] \u2013 [https://archive.org/details/1508288358bsb11304504 VI]\n  | location    = G\u00fctersloh\n  | publisher   = [[Bertelsmann]]\n  | language    = de\n  | ref         = harv\n }}\n\n''Online sources''\n* {{cite web\n| last = Bischof\n| first = Walter F.\n| url = https://webdocs.cs.ualberta.ca/~wfb/cantatas/248II.html\n| title = BWV 248II Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend / Weihnachts-Oratorium I\n| website = University of Alberta\n| year = 2019\n| accessdate = 4 December 2019\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| last = Dahn\n| first = Luke\n| url = http://www.bach-chorales.com/BWV0248_12.htm\n| title = BWV 248.12\n| year = 2019\n| website = bach-chorales.com\n| accessdate = 4 December 2019\n| ref = {{sfnref|Dahn 12|2019}}\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| last = Dahn\n| first = Luke\n| url = http://www.bach-chorales.com/BWV0248_17.htm\n| title = BWV 248.17\n| year = 2019\n| website = bach-chorales.com\n| accessdate = 4 December 2019\n| ref = {{sfnref|Dahn 17|2019}}\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| last = Dahn\n| first = Luke\n| url = http://www.bach-chorales.com/BWV0248_23.htm\n| title = BWV 248.23\n| year = 2019\n| website = bach-chorales.com\n| accessdate = 4 December 2019\n| ref = {{sfnref|Dahn 23|2019}}\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| last = Dellal\n| first = Pamela\n| authorlink = Pamela Dellal\n| url = http://www.emmanuelmusic.org/notes_translations/translations_cantata/t_bwv248-2.htm\n| title = BWV 248-II \u2013 \"Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend\" \n| year = 2019\n| website = [[Emmanuel Music]]\n| accessdate = 4 December 2019\n| ref = harv\n}}\n<!--\n* {{cite web\n| last = Hofmann\n| first = Klaus\n| url = https://www.carusmedia.com/images-intern/medien/30/3124853/3124853x.pdf\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach / Weihnachtsoratorium / Christmas Oratorio\n| website = [[Carus-Verlag]]\n| year = 2005\n| page = V\n| accessdate = 15 November 2013\n| ref = harv\n}}-->\n* {{cite web\n| last = Rathey\n| first = Markus\n| url = https://ism.yale.edu/sites/default/files/files/Johann%20Sebastian%20Bach.pdf\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach's Mass in B Minor: The Greatest Artwork of All Times and All People\n| website = ism.yale.edu\n| date = 18 April 2003\n| accessdate = 14 November 2013\n| ref = {{sfnref|Rathey|2003}}\n}}\n<!--\n* {{cite web\n| last = Sch\u00f6newolf\n| first = Markus\n| url = https://schoenewolf.com/bach-weihnachtsoratorium/\n| title = J. S. Bach, Weihnachtsoratorium: Werkeinf\u00fchrung und Libretto\n| website = schoenewolf.com\n| date = 2019\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 15 November 2013\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| url = https://www.konzerthaus-dortmund.de/page/MediaLib/file/Programmheft/200809/Programm-Weihnachtsoratorium.pdf\n| title = Ah! Lord, how shall I meet Thee\n| website = [[Konzerthaus Dortmund]]\n| date = 6 December 2008\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 15 November 2018\n| ref = {{sfnref|Konzerthaus Dortmund|2008}}\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| url = https://hymnary.org/text/o_lord_how_shall_i_meet_thee\n| title = Ah! Lord, how shall I meet Thee\n| website = hymnary.org\n| accessdate = 16 December 2017\n| ref = {{sfnref|Hymnary|2019}}\n}}-->\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Christmas Oratorio}}\n* {{IMSLP|work=Weihnachtsoratorium, BWV 248 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|cname=Weihnachtsoratorium, BWV 248}}\n* Markus Sch\u00f6newolf: [https://schoenewolf.com/bach-weihnachtsoratorium/ Weihnachtsoratorium] schoenewolf.com\n* [http://www.bachdiskographie.de/textkangeist/bwv248_IItext.html BWV 248 / II] bachdiskographie.de\n<!--\n* {{IMSLP|work=T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten!, BWV 214 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|cname=T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten!, BWV 214}}\n* {{cite web\n| last = Mincham\n| first = Julian\n| url = http://www.jsbachcantatas.com/documents/chapter-95-bwv-214.htm\n| title = Chapter 95 BWV 214 T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten! / Resound Drums, ring out Trumpets!\n| publisher = jsbachcantatas\n| accessdate = 7 June 2013\n}}-->\n\n{{Masses, Magnificat, Passions and Oratorios by Johann Sebastian Bach}}\n{{Church cantatas by Johann Sebastian Bach}}\n{{Bach cantatas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Und es waren Hirten in derselben Gegend'', BWV 248 II}}\n\n[[Category:Church cantatas by Johann Sebastian Bach]]\n[[Category:1734 compositions]]\n[[Category:Christmas cantatas]]\n", "name_user": "Vami IV", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e12", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Und_es_waren_Hirten_in_derselben_Gegend,_BWV_248_II"}
{"title_page": "Slobodan Praljak", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Slobodan Praljak\n| image         = Slobodan Praljak.jpg\n| caption       = Praljak in 2017\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1945|01|02|df=y}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2017|11|29|1945|01|02|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[\u010capljina]], [[Independent State of Croatia]]\n| death_place   = [[The Hague]], [[Netherlands]]\n| module        = {{Infobox person|child=yes|death_cause=[[Suicide by poisoning]]}}\n| allegiance    = {{flag|Croatia}}<br />\n| branch        = [[Croatian Army]]<br />[[Croatian Defence Council]]\n| serviceyears  = 1991\u20131995\n| rank          = [[General]]\n| servicenumber =\n| unit          =\n| commands      =\n| battles       = {{plainlist |\n* [[Croatian War of Independence]]\n* [[Bosnian War]]\n* [[Croat\u2013Bosniak War]] }}\n| battles_label =\n| awards        =\n| relations     = \n| spouse        = Ka\u0107u\u0161a Babi\u0107\n| laterwork     = Professor, film and theatre director, businessman, writer\n| signature     =\n| website       = \n}}\n\n'''Slobodan Praljak''' ({{IPA-sh|slob\u01d2dan pr\u01ce\u02d0\u028eak|hr}}; 2 January 1945 \u2013 29 November 2017) was a [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Croat]] general who served in the [[Croatian Army]] and the [[Croatian Defence Council]], an army of the [[Croatian Republic of Herzeg-Bosnia]], between 1992 and 1995. Praljak was found guilty of committing violations of the [[laws of war]], [[crimes against humanity]] and breaches of the [[Geneva Conventions]] during the [[Croat\u2013Bosniak War]] by the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]] (ICTY) in 2017.<ref name=\"ICTY2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/x/cases/prlic/acjug/en/171129-judgement-summary.pdf|title=Trial Judgement Summary for Prli\u0107 et al.|date=29 November 2017|publisher=ICTY|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nPraljak voluntarily joined the newly formed [[Croatian Armed Forces]] after the outbreak of the [[Croatian War of Independence]] in 1991. Before and after the war he was an engineer, a television and theatre director, as well as a businessman.<ref name=\"Ve\u010dernji\">{{cite news|author=Ivica Rado\u0161|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/slobodan-praljak-presuda-haag-sarajevo-general-1210985|title=Tko je bio Slobodan Praljak? Slao je oru\u017eje Bo\u0161njacima u opkoljeno Sarajevo|trans-title=Who was Slobodan Praljak? He sent weapons to Bosnians in the besieged Sarajevo|date=29 November 2017|publisher=[[Ve\u010dernji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Rferl\">{{cite news|author=Andrey Shary|author-link=Andrey Shary|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/commentary-the-poisoned-general-slobodan-praljak-icty/28888298.html|title=The Poisoned General|date=30 November 2017|publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref> Praljak was indicted by, and voluntarily surrendered to, the ICTY in 2004.<ref name=\"TrialIn\">{{cite web|url=https://trialinternational.org/latest-post/slobodan-praljak/|title=Slobodan Praljak|date=6 May 2016|publisher=Trial International|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> In 2013, he was convicted for [[war crime]]s against the [[Bosniak]] population during the Croat\u2013Bosniak War alongside five other Bosnian Croat officials,<ref name=\"ICTY\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/x/cases/prlic/ind/en/prl-ii040304e.htm|title=Prlic et al. Initial Indictment|date=2 March 2004|publisher=ICTY}}</ref><ref name=\"LAT\">{{cite news|url=http://beta.latimes.com/world/la-fg-croatia-slobadan-praljak-20171129-story.html|title='I am not a war criminal,' convicted Bosnian Croat cries as he takes a fatal dose of poison|date=29 November 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=29 November 2017|quote=Ironically, Praljak, who surrendered to the tribunal in April 2004 and had already been jailed for 13 years, could have soon walked free because those who are convicted are generally released after serving two-thirds of their sentences.}}</ref> and was sentenced to 20 years in jail (minus the time he had already spent in detention).<ref>{{cite news|author=Mike Corder|url=http://www.news1130.com/2013/05/29/un-war-crimes-tribunal-convicts-6-bosnian-croats-of-persecution-of-muslims-during-bosnian-war/|title=UN war crimes tribunal convicts 6 Bosnian Croats of persecution of Muslims during Bosnian war|date=29 May 2013|publisher=News1130}}</ref> Upon hearing the guilty verdict upheld in November 2017, Praljak stated that he rejected the verdict of the court, and committed [[suicide by poisoning]] in the courtroom.<ref name=\"icty-statement\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/en/press/statement-on-passing-of-slobodan-praljak|title=Statement on passing of Slobodan Praljak|date=29 November 2017|publisher=ICTY|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"om.nl\">{{cite web|url=https://www.om.nl/@101281/preliminary-results/|title=Preliminary results autopsy Slobodan Praljak|publisher=[[Openbaar Ministerie]]|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|author=Owen Bowcott|title=Bosnian Croat war criminal dies after taking poison in UN courtroom|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2017/nov/29/un-war-crimes-defendant-claims-to-drink-poison-at-trial-in-hague-slobodan-praljak|date=29 November 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|author1=Stephanie van den Berg|author2=Bart H. Meijer|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-warcrimes-bosnia/bosnian-croat-war-crimes-convict-dies-after-taking-poison-in-u-n-court-idUKKBN1DT1E1|title=Bosnian Croat war crimes convict dies after taking 'poison' in U.N. court|date=29 November 2017|agency=Reuters|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and career ==\nSlobodan Praljak was born on 2 January 1945 in [[\u010capljina]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]. His father Mirko worked for the security agency [[OZNA]].<ref name=\"Ve\u010dernji\"/> \n\nPraljak attended high school in [[Li\u0161tica]] with the future Croatian Defense Minister [[Gojko \u0160u\u0161ak]]. He had three university degrees. In 1970, he graduated as an [[electrical engineer]] at the [[Faculty of Electrical Engineering in Zagreb]] with a [[GPA]] of 4.5/5. In 1971, he graduated from the [[Zagreb Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences]], majoring in philosophy and sociology. In 1972, he graduated from the [[Zagreb Academy of Dramatic Art]].<ref name=\"Jutarnji\"/><ref name=\"SDalmacija\"/>\n\nAt first, Praljak worked as a professor and manager of the electronics laboratory at the Nikola Tesla Vocational High School in Zagreb, then lectured on philosophy and sociology,<ref name=\"Jutarnji\">{{cite news|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/tko-je-bio-slobodan-praljak-imao-je-tri-diplome-kontroverzan-ratni-put-ali-i-nevjerojatnu-obiteljsku-pricu-sa-suprugom-i-velikim-prijateljem/6795618/|title=Tko je bio Slobodan Praljak: Imao je tri diplome, kontroverzan ratni put, ali i nevjerojatnu obiteljsku pri\u010du sa suprugom i velikim prijateljem...|trans-title=Who was Slobodan Praljak: He had three diplomas, a controversial war trail, and an incredible family story with his wife and great friend...|date=29 November 2017|publisher=[[Jutarnji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref> and after 1973 was a freelance artist.<ref name=\"SDalmacija\">{{cite news|url=https://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/novosti/hrvatska/clanak/id/519404/tko-je-bio-general-praljak-imao-je-tri-diplome-bio-je-i-slobodni-umjetnik-a-91-dragovoljno-odlazi-na-ratiste-privatni-zivot-obiljezila-mu-je-nevjerojatna-prica|title=Tko je bio general Praljak? Imao je tri diplome, bio je i 'slobodni umjetnik', a '91. dragovoljno odlazi na rati\u0161te; Privatni \u017eivot obilje\u017eila mu je nevjerojatna pri\u010da|trans-title=Who was General Praljak? He had three diplomas, he was also a 'free artist', and '91. he voluntarily goes to the battlefield; His private life marked an incredible story|date=29 November 2017|work=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> Praljak was also a theatre director in theatres in Zagreb, [[Osijek]] and [[Mostar]]. He directed the television series ''Blesan i Tulipan'' [Blesan and Tulipan], television dramas ''Novela od Stanca'' and ''Sarga\u0161ko more'' [Sargasso Sea], documentaries ''Smrt psa'' (1980) [Death of a Dog], ''Sand\u017eak'' and ''Duhan'' [Tobacco] (both in 1990), and film ''Povratak Katarine Ko\u017eul'' (1989) [Return of Katarina Ko\u017eul].<ref name=\"Ve\u010dernji\" /><ref name=\"Jutarnji\"/><ref name=\"Index\">{{cite news|author=Oriana Ivkovi\u0107 Novokmet|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/tko-je-bio-slobodan-praljak-osudjeni-ratni-zlocinac-koji-je-zaradio-milijune-nakon-rata/1010602.aspx|title=Tko je bio Slobodan Praljak? Osu\u0111eni ratni zlo\u010dinac koji je zaradio milijune nakon rata|trans-title=Who was Slobodan Praljak? A guilty war criminal who has earned millions after the war|date=29 November 2017|publisher=[[Index.hr]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Military activity during the Croatian War of Independence and Croat\u2013Bosniak War ==\nPraljak drew public attention in September 1991 when he voluntarily joined the newly formed [[Armed Forces of the Republic of Croatia|Croatian Armed Forces]] after the outbreak of the [[Croatian War of Independence]]. He formed a unit composed of the Zagreb artists and intellectuals with whom he held positions in [[Sunja, Sisak-Moslavina County|Sunja]].<ref name=\"Jutarnji\" /> After the [[Vance plan#Implementation Agreement|Sarajevo Agreement]], by 3 April 1992, he was made [[major general]],<ref name=\"TrialIn\"/> received a number of responsibilities in the [[Ministry of Defence (Croatia)|Ministry of Defence]], and became one of the 14 members of the Croatian National Defence Council and a member of the Croatian State Commission for Relations with [[United Nations Protection Force]] (UNPROFOR). He was the High Representative of the Ministry of Defence, and since 13 May 1993, representative of the Ministry of Defence in the [[Croatian Republic of Herzeg-Bosnia]] and [[Croatian Defence Council]] (HVO).<ref name=\"Jutarnji\" /> Praljak petitioned [[Alija Izetbegovi\u0107]] to unblock [[Sarajevo]] but his propositions were rejected. From 24 July to 8 November 1993, Praljak was the Chief of Staff of the Croatian Defence Council. In spite of the Croat-Muslim conflict in the [[Croat\u2013Bosniak War]], he sent a truck full of weapons to [[Siege of Sarajevo|besieged Sarajevo]] to help Bosniaks. He also allowed the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|UNHCR]]'s humanitarian convoy through to [[Mostar]], which was stopped in [[\u010citluk]].<ref name=\"Ve\u010dernji\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/x/cases/prlic/custom5/en/110331a.pdf|title=Slobodan Praljak's Redacted Final Trial Brief|date=31 March 2011|publisher=ICTY|pages=42\u201343, 86, 177\u2013178}}</ref>\n\nPraljak was accused of failing to prevent the armed forces from committing many crimes of which he was informed and that he could foresee, including removing and placing in detention the Muslim population of [[Prozor, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Prozor]] from July through August 1993, murders in Mostar municipality, the destruction of buildings in East Mostar (including the mosques and the [[Stari Most]]), attacking and wounding of members of international organisations, the destruction and looting of property in [[Gornji Vakuf]] in January 1993, Ra\u0161tani in August 1993, and [[Stupni Do]] in October 1993.<ref name=\"Sheet17\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/x/cases/prlic/cis/en/cis_prlic_al_en.pdf|title=Case Information Sheet: Prli\u0107 et al.|publisher=ICTY|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> During 1993, General Praljak was in charge of the [[Dretelj camp]] where Bosniak men were brutalized, starved, and some killed.<ref name=\"Vulliamy\">{{cite news|last1=Vulliamy|first1=Ed||author-link=Ed Vulliamy|title=The day I came face to face with General Slobodan Praljak in The Hague|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2017/nov/29/the-day-i-came-face-to-face-with-general-slobodan-praljak-in-the-hague|date=29 November 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> \n\nPraljak was accused of ordering the destruction of Mostar's [[Stari Most]] in November 1993, an act which [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia|ICTY]] ruled had \"caused disproportionate damage to the Muslim civilian population\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/un-war-crimes-court-yugoslavia-final-verdict/28885760.html|title=War Criminal Dies After 'Taking Poison' In Hague Courtroom|date=29 November 2017|publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|access-date=30 November 2017}}</ref> However, ICTY agreed that the bridge was a legitimate military target.<ref name=\"Guardian\" /> During the trial, Praljak denied the accusation because in the same month when the destruction occurred, he came into conflict with the commander of the HVO's so-called ''Punishment Battalion'' [[Mladen Naletili\u0107 Tuta]] which resulted in his resignation from the positions of HVO's Chief of Staff, one day before the destruction of the bridge. He said that the bridge was demolished by activation of the explosive charge set on the left bank of the [[Neretva]], where the [[Army of the Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Army of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] was located.<ref name=\"Jutarnji\" /><ref>{{cite news|author=Gordana Knezevi\u0107|author-link=Gordana Knezevi\u0107|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/balkans-without-borders-mostar-bridge-praljiak/28884107.html|title=The Cultured Destroyers of Culture|date=29 November 2017|publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> In addition to the responsibility and whether it was a legitimate military target, ICTY also examined whether the earlier siege by [[Yugoslav People's Army|JNA]] and Bosnian Serb forces contributed to the bridge's collapse.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f2KrCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA315|title=Bosnia and the Destruction of Cultural Heritage|publisher=Routledge|author=Helen Walasek, contributions by Richard Carlton, Amra Had\u017eimuhamedovi\u0107, Valery Perry, Tina Wik|page=315|isbn=9781317172994|date=2016-03-03}}</ref> Praljak retired from military service at his own request on 1 December 1995.<ref name=\"SDalmacija\"/>\n\n== Postwar career ==\nAfter the war, Praljak became a businessman.<ref name=\"SDalmacija\"/> In 1995, Praljak co-founded a company with his brother Zoran called Oktavijan. His company initially produced films, video, and television programs and published Praljak\u2019s books. It later engaged in real estate business by managing a business complex ''Centar 2000'' in Zagreb. Since 2005, the company is owned and managed by his stepson Nikola Babi\u0107 Praljak.<ref name=\"Jutarnji17\">{{cite news|author=Tomislav Kukec|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/najneobicnija-obiteljska-prica-s-ovih-prostora-haaskom-sudu-duguje-tri-milijuna-eura-a-u-zagrebu-gradi-velebni-centar-od-14-milijuna-eura/5816487/|title=Najneobi\u010dnija Pri\u010da S Ovih Prostora: Haa\u0161kom sudu duguje tri milijuna eura, a u Zagrebu gradi velebni centar od 14 milijuna eura|trans-title=Most unusual story from the region: Owes three million euros to the Hague Tribunal, and in Zagreb is building a big center worth 14 million euros|date=26 March 2017|work=[[Jutarnji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> In 2011 it had around 22 million [[Croatian kuna|kunas]] of revenue.<ref name=\"Jutarnji2012\">{{cite news|author=Kre\u0161imir \u017dabec|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/ministarstvo-generalu-praljku-vase-knjige-o-ratu-spadaju-u-sund-i-pornografiju-platit-cete-628.726-kuna-poreza/1537959/|title=Ministarstvo generalu Praljku: Va\u0161e knjige o ratu spadaju u \u0161und i pornografiju, platit \u0107ete 628.726 kuna poreza!|date=4 July 2012|publisher=[[Jutarnji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> Praljak was also a co-owner of Liberan, a company that has a share in [[Ljubu\u0161ki]] Tobacco Factory,<ref name=\"Index\" /> and owned other shares in few other companies.<ref name=\"Jutarnji17\" /> In 2008, the [[Ministry of Culture (Croatia)|Croatian Ministry of Culture]] deemed that 18 of his works about the Croatian War of Independence, Bosnian War, and relations between Croatia and Bosnia and Herzegovina were not books but brochures of worthless literature,<ref name=\"Jutarnji2012\"/> and in 2013 the [[Ministry of Finance (Croatia)|Ministry of Finance]] made an enforcement charge of 435 thousand kunas.<ref name=\"Sata\">{{cite new|url=https://www.24sata.hr/news/tko-je-slobodan-praljak-bio-u-tri-vojske-i-zavrsio-tri-fakulteta-550352|title=Tko je Slobodan Praljak? Bio u tri vojske i zavr\u0161io tri fakulteta|trans-title=Who was Slobodan Praljak? He was in three armies and finished three faculties|date=29 November 2017|work=[[24sata (Croatia)|24sata]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref> In total, he authored 25 works.<ref name=\"Jutarnji17\"/> Since 2012, The Hague Tribunal's secretariat requested Praljak to recover defence costs of around EUR 2.8-3.3 million, as they estimated that he had assets and shares worth EUR 6.5 million which allowed him to fund the costs of his defence. Praljak and his lawyer refused the estimation statement because he had no property in his name even from the beginning of the trial.<ref name=\"Sata\"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Vanja Nezirovi\u0107|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/luksuzno-carstvo-generala-praljak-svu-imovinu-prebacio-na-sina-i-tvrdi-da-nema-bas-nista/1554003/|title=Luksuzno Carstvo Generala: Praljak svu imovinu prebacio na sina i tvrdi da nema ba\u0161 ni\u0161ta!|trans-title=Luxury Empire of General: Praljak all assets transferred to his son and says that he has nothing!|date=31 August 2012|work=[[Jutarnji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/neobicni-zahtjeva-s-haaskog-suda-mozete-li-nam-pomoci-locirati-imovinu-generala-praljka-duzan-nam-je-28-milijuna-eura/5800395/|title=Neobi\u010dni Zahtjev S Ha\u0161kog Suda: 'Mo\u017eete li nam pomo\u0107i locirati imovinu generala Praljka... du\u017ean nam je 2,8 milijuna eura!'|trans-title=An Unusual Request from the Hague Tribunal: \"Can you help us locate the property of General Praljak ... he owes us 2.8 million euros!\"|date=22 March 2017|work=[[Jutarnji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== ICTY indictment ==\nPraljak was among six accused by the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]] (ICTY), in relation to the [[Croatian Republic of Herzeg-Bosnia]].<ref name=\"ICTY\" /> On 5 April 2004, he voluntarily surrendered and was transferred to the ICTY.<ref name=\"TrialIn\"/> In his indictment it was alleged that Praljak as a senior military official commanded, directly and indirectly, the Herceg-Bosna/HVO armed forces which committed mass war crimes against Bosnian Muslim population in 8 municipalities in Bosnia and Herzegovina during a [[joint criminal enterprise]] between 1992 and 1994. In his role as a high-ranking official in the Ministry of Defence, he was closely involved in all aspects of not only the Herceg-Bosna/HVO military planning and operations but the actions of the Herceg-Bosna/HVO civilian police too.<ref name=\"ICTY\" /> On 6 April, he appeared before ICTY and pleaded not guilty.<ref name=\"TrialIn\"/> He chose to defend himself without a lawyer.<ref name=\"Vulliamy\"/>\n\nThe indictment charged on the basis of their individual and superior criminal responsibility, but subsequently in judgment only on the basis of individual criminal responsibility. Praljak was found guilty on (taken from the UN press release 2004, 2017):\n{{quote|\n* four counts of grave breaches of the [[Geneva Conventions]] (willful killing; unlawful deportation, transfer and confinement of a civilian; inhuman treatment; extensive destruction of property and appropriation of property, not justified by military necessity and carried out unlawfully and wantonly).\n* six counts of violations of the [[Law of war|laws or customs of war]] (cruel treatment; unlawful labour; destruction or wilful damage done to institutions dedicated to religion or education; plunder of public or private property; unlawful attack on civilians; unlawful infliction of terror on civilians)\n* five counts of [[crimes against humanity]] (persecutions on political, racial and religious grounds; murder; deportation; imprisonment; inhumane acts)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/en/press/jadranko-prlic-bruno-stojic-slobodan-praljak-milivoj-petkovic-valentin-coric-and-berislav-0|title=Press Release: Jadranko Prlic, Bruno Stojic, Slobodan Praljak, Milivoj Petkovic, Valentin Coric and Berislav Pusic|date=6 April 2004|publisher=ICTY|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Sheet17\"/>}}\n\nThe trial began on 26 April 2006. On 29 May 2013 the Trial Chamber judgement sentenced him to 20 years of imprisonment (the sentence took into account the time he had already spent in detention), and on 28 June 2013, Praljak filed an appeal.<ref name=\"TrialIn\"/> On 29 November 2017, the ICTY trial was concluded finding him guilty, and although some parts of his conviction were overturned, the judge did not reduce the initial sentence of 20 years.<ref name=\"ICTY2017\"/><ref name=\"Guardian\" /><ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|author=Marlise Simons|author-link=Marlise Simons|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/29/world/europe/bosnian-war-croatia.html|title=Croatian War Criminal Dies After Swallowing Poison in Court|date=29 November 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref> He was charged with crimes against \"humanity, violations of the laws or customs of war, and grave breaches of the Geneva Conventions\", also \"extensive appropriation of property not justified by military necessity\" and \"plunder of public or private property through the third category of joint criminal enterprise liability\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/en/press/the-icty-renders-its-final-judgement-in-the-prli%C4%87-et-al-appeal-case|title=The ICTY renders its final judgement in the Prli\u0107 et al. appeal case|date=29 November 2017|publisher=ICTY|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> on which given his [[command responsibility]] he failed to act and prevent.<ref name=\"Rferl\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Praljak: Police investigate Hague trial suicide|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42177772|date=30 November 2017|publisher=BBC|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> He was acquitted of some charges related to the destruction of [[Stari Most]].<ref name=\"Rferl\"/><ref name=\"LAT\" /> As he had already served more than two-thirds of the sentence in jail (around 13 years and several months), he would probably have been released soon.<ref name=\"LAT\" /><ref>{{cite news|author=Davor Ivankovi\u0107|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/slobodan-praljak-haag-sloboda-kazna-otrov-1210894|title=Da nije popio otrov, Praljak bi uskoro bio na slobodi|trans-title=If he did not drank the poison, Praljak would soon be at liberty|date=29 November 2017|publisher=[[Ve\u010dernji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nOn 29 November 2017, during the pronouncement of the appeal judgment against him, Praljak addressed the judges, saying: \"Judges, Slobodan Praljak is not a war criminal. With disdain, I reject your verdict!\"<ref name=\"HRT\">{{cite news|url=http://vijesti.hrt.hr/417745/sudac-agius-ovo-je-bio-vrlo-dug-i-slozen-postupak|title=Na izricanju presude Slobodan Praljak popio otrov i preminuo|trans-title=At the pronouncement of the verdict Slobodan Praljak drank the poison and passed away|date=29 November 2017|publisher=[[Croatian Radiotelevision]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Post\">{{cite news|author=Willa Frej|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/slobodan-praljak-dies-poison_us_5a1ebb4fe4b0cb0e917cfe4b?ncid=inblnkushpmg00000009|title=Former Bosnian Croat Official on Trial For War Crimes Dies After Drinking Poison in Court|date=29 November 2017|work=HuffPost|access-date=1 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"aljaz\">{{cite news|title=Slobodan Praljak umro u bolnici|trans-title=Slobodan Praljak died in hospital|url=http://balkans.aljazeera.net/vijesti/slobodan-praljak-umro-u-bolnici|work=Al Jazeera Balkans|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=1 December 2017|language=Serbo-Croatian}}</ref> He then drank what he said was poison,<ref name=\"HRT\" /><ref name=\"Post\" /> leading presiding judge Carmel Agius to suspend the hearings.<ref name=\"Reuters\" /> ICTY medical staff transported Praljak to nearby HMC Hospital,<ref name=\"icty-statement\" /> where he died.<ref name=\"LAT\" /><ref name=\"om.nl\"/> The Dutch authorities declared the courtroom a crime scene and launched an investigation.<ref name=\"Reuters\" /><ref name=\"icty-statement\"/> His body was cremated in Zagreb in a private ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/report-croat-war-criminal-cremated-after-death-at-hague/2017/12/09/818660ec-dcdf-11e7-a241-0848315642d0_story.html?tid=hybrid_collaborative_1_na|title=Report: Croat war criminal cremated after death at Hague|date=9 December 2017|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Reaction ===\nFormer ICTY judges [[Wolfgang Schomburg]] and [[Richard Goldstone]] commented that \"it is a tragedy that someone in such a situation has taken their own life\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Zoran Arbutina|url=http://www.dw.com/en/icty-hague-tribunal-ends-prosecutions-of-yugoslav-war-crimes-but-legacy-lingers/a-41587892|title=ICTY Hague Tribunal ends prosecutions of Yugoslav war crimes but legacy lingers|date=29 November 2017|publisher=Deutsche Welle|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> Goldstone added: \"In a way, the victims are deprived of this deed. They did not get full justice.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nacional.hr/goldstone-praljak-je-uskratio-pravdu-zrtvama/|title=Goldstone: 'Praljak je uskratio pravdu \u017ertvama'|trans-title=Goldstone: 'Praljak has denied justice to the victims'|date=1 December 2017|publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref> [[Martin Bell]] described Praljak as a \"theatrical character\" who \"died in a theatrical way\".<ref name=\"Sky\">{{cite news|author=Alan McGuinness|title=War criminal Slobodan Praljak dies after taking poison in court|url=https://news.sky.com/story/war-criminal-slobodan-praljak-dies-after-taking-poison-in-court-11148960|date=29 November 2017|publisher=Sky News|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref> [[Andrey Shary]] for [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] noted that \"Praljak's [[Seppuku|samurai final act]] might evoke respect or sympathy\", but \"individual perceptions of honor don't always coincide with correctness\".<ref name=\"Rferl\"/> \n\nWriting in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', journalist Harry de Quetteville opined that the defiant suicide was \"the most dramatic proof possible of a very uncomfortable reality: many in the Balkans refuse to accept that the horrific ethnic cleansing of the 1990s was wrong\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=de Quetteville|first1=Harry|title=Balkans suicide: the poison is not just in court but across the whole region|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/29/balkans-suicide-poison-not-just-court-across-whole-region/|accessdate=30 November 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=29 November 2017}}</ref> Former [[United States Ambassador-at-Large for War Crimes Issues|US Ambassador for War Crimes Issues]] [[Stephen Rapp]] compared Praljak's suicide by poisoning to that of another war crimes convict, [[Hermann G\u00f6ring]], noting that in both cases the verdict nevertheless \"stands for all history in establishing the facts and in showing that the perpetrators of atrocities will be held to account\".<ref name=\"Biddle\">{{cite news|last=Biddle|first=Jo|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20171201-un-court-closes-under-cloud-war-criminals-suicide|title=UN court closes under cloud of Slobodan Praljak's suicide|date=1 December 2017|work=Agence France Presse|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Regional reaction ====\nThe [[Croatian government]] offered condolences to Praljak's family and said the ICTY misrepresented its officials in the 1990s. Prime Minister [[Andrej Plenkovi\u0107]] stated that Praljak's suicide illustrated the \"deep moral injustice towards the six Croats from Bosnia and Herzegovina and the Croatian people\".<ref>{{cite web|title=PM: Praljak's act speaks of deep moral injustice towards Bosnian Croats|url=https://vlada.gov.hr/news/pm-praljak-s-act-speaks-of-deep-moral-injustice-towards-bosnian-croats/22949|date=29 November 2017|publisher=[[Government of Croatia]]|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref> All the party caucuses of the [[Croatian Parliament]] except the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia|SDP]] and [[Civic Liberal Alliance|GLAS]] issued a joint statement declaring that ICTY's verdict did not respect the \"historical truths, facts and evidence\", and that it was \"unjust and unacceptable\", adding that Praljak symbolically warned of all the verdicts' injustice with his suicide. They expressed their condolences to the families of victims of crimes committed during the [[Bosnian War]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://vijesti.hrt.hr/417952/jandrokovic-procitao-zajednicku-izjavu-presude-ne-uvazavaju-povijesne-istine |title=Jandrokovi\u0107 pro\u010ditao zajedni\u010dku izjavu: Presude ne uva\u017eavaju povijesne istine |trans-title=Jandrokovi\u0107 read a joint statement: The judgments do not respect the historical truths |date=30 November 2017 |publisher=Croatian Radiotelevision |language=Serbo-Croatian |accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> Croatian president [[Kolinda Grabar-Kitarovi\u0107]] expressed her condolences to Praljak's family, calling him \"a man who preferred to die rather than live as a convict for crimes he did not commit\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://vijesti.hrt.hr/417929/obracanje-javnosti-predsjednice-rh-u-povodu-presude-haskog-suda|title=Predsjednica: Hrvatski narod prvi se odupro velikosrpskoj agresiji brane\u0107i svoju opstojnost i opstojnost BiH|trans-title=President: The Croatian people first resisted the Greater Serbia aggression by defending its survival and the survival of BiH|date=30 November 2017|publisher=Croatian Radiotelevision|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> [[Miroslav Tu\u0111man]] stated it was a \"consequence of his moral position not to accept the verdict that has nothing to do with justice or reality\".<ref name=\"Sky\" />\n\nThe [[List of Bosniak members of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosniak member]] of the [[Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Bakir Izetbegovi\u0107]], said that Praljak was led to suicide by the joint criminal enterprise,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/izetbegovic-praljka-je-upropastio-projekt-udruzenog-zlocinackog-pothvata-foto-20171129|title=Izetbegovi\u0107: Praljka je upropastio projekt udru\u017eenog zlo\u010dina\u010dkog pothvata|trans-title=Izetbegovi\u0107: Praljak was ruined by the project of a joint criminal enterprise|date=29 November 2017|publisher=Tportal.hr|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> while Croat [[Chairman of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Chairman]] [[Dragan \u010covi\u0107]] stated that Praljak had sacrificed his life to prove his innocence.<ref name=\"LAT\" /> Serbian President [[Aleksandar Vu\u010di\u0107]] said he would not mock Praljak's suicide but has criticized the reaction of Croatian officials, stating that it would have been unacceptable for him to praise a convicted war criminal as a hero or to denounce an ICTY verdict.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.b92.net/info/vesti/index.php?yyyy=2017&mm=11&dd=30&nav_category=64&nav_id=1330955|title=Vu\u010di\u0107 o Praljku: Ne bih se rugao i nazivao kukavi\u010dkim|trans-title=Vucic about Praljak: I would not mock and called it cowardly|date=30 November 2017|publisher=[[B92]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> The Serbian politician [[Vojislav \u0160e\u0161elj]] commented that, although he was an enemy, it was a \"heroic move worthy of respect\" and there should have been more such strong blows to the tribunal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espreso.rs/vesti/hronika/202957/junacki-cin-za-postovanje-seselj-za-espreso-komentarise-samoubistvo-hrvatskog-generala-usred-haskog-tribunala-video?ref=ext_kurir|title=Juna\u010dki \u010din za po\u0161tovanje! \u0160e\u0161elj za Espreso komentari\u0161e samoubistvo hrvatskog generala usred Ha\u0161kog tribunala|trans-title=Heroic move for respect! \u0160e\u0161elj for Espreso comments suicide of Croatian general in the middle of Hague tribunal|date=29 November 2017|work=Espreso.rs|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> \n\nAlmost a thousand Bosnian Croats gathered in the Mostar and \u010capljina squares to [[candlelight vigil|light candles]] to pay respect to Praljak.<ref name=\"LAT\" /><ref>{{cite news|author=Andrew MacDowall|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/02/slobodan-praljak-suicide-reopens-old-wounds-bosnia|title=Slobodan Praljak's suicide reopens old wounds in Bosnia|date=2 December 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> On December 11, 2017, a commemoration for Slobodan Praljak was held in Zagreb. The event was attended by two thousand people, including Government ministers [[Damir Krsti\u010devi\u0107]] and Tomo Medved (as private citizens), a number of MPs, mostly from the [[Croatian Democratic Union]] party, and some retired army officers that participated in the 1990s war. In the evening, a religious ceremony was also held at a Catholic church. During the same day, members of the [[Youth Initiative for Human Rights]] made a commemoration for the victims of Croatian forces urging condemnation of that period policies.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sven Milekic|url=https://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/zagreb-commemorates-praljak-by-rejecting-verdict-12-11-2017|title=War Criminal Praljak\u2019s Death Commemorated in Croatia|date=11 December 2017|work=Balkan Insight|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Darko Bandic|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/croat-nationalists-honor-general-convicted-of-war-crimes/2017/12/11/32bf4970-de6e-11e7-b2e9-8c636f076c76_story.html|title=Croat nationalists honor general convicted of war crimes|date=11 December 2017|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nPresident Grabar-Kitarovi\u0107 has been pressured to take away wartime decorations from Praljak and other convicted officials, but she refused to do so stating that they received it for defence against Serbian aggression, adding that \"such practice has not been implemented so far, except in the case of verdicts made by the Croatian courts\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/tihomir-blaskic-dario-kordic-odlikovanja-1213585|title=Odlikovanja RH nisu oduzeta ni Tihomiru Bla\u0161ki\u0107u, Dariju Kordi\u0107u...|trans-title=The Republic of Croatia decorations have not been taken away either from Tihomir Bla\u0161ki\u0107, Darijo Kordic...|date=12 December 2017|publisher=[[Ve\u010dernji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Investigation ===\n{{update section|date=November 2018}}\nA preliminary [[autopsy]] determined that Praljak had [[cyanide poisoning|poisoned]] himself with [[potassium cyanide]], which caused his heart to fail.<ref name=\"om.nl\" /> How the poison was obtained and brought into the courtroom is to be the subject of an official investigation.<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite news|author=Mike Corder|url=http://time.com/5044356/slobodan-praljak-war-crimes-poison/|title=The Container That Croat War Criminal Praljak Drank From Held a Deadly Chemical, Prosecutor Says|date=1 December 2017|work=Time|accessdate=1 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031537/http://time.com/5044356/slobodan-praljak-war-crimes-poison/|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Praljak's lawyer Nika Pinter suggested that he may have committed suicide because he could not accept being convicted as a war criminal and that the act had been long-planned.<ref>{{cite news|author=Darko Bandic|url=https://www.apnews.com/26667453debf458f92b6ea8a7e5bc799/Lawyer:--Convicted-Croat-general-might-have-planned-death|title=Lawyer: Convicted Croat general might have planned death|date=5 December 2017|work=Associated Press|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> \n\nThe cyanide that Praljak took was not listed as a prohibited substance under Dutch law.\n\n\u201cWith regards to the investigation concerning assistance in the commission of suicide, the Dutch authorities conducted a thorough investigation of how Praljak could get ahold of the cyanide. Witnesses were interviewed, video materials watched, rooms in which Praljak stayed were checked and numerous materials inspected. However, no information was found concerning the question on how Praljak came into possession of that substance,\u201d the prosecutors\u2019 report said. The report added that video surveillance recordings did not show if Praljak carried the vial of poison with him or if it was handed to him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://balkaninsight.com/2018/11/02/slobodan-praljak-court-suicide-source-of-poison-unclear-11-02-2018/|title=Slobodan Praljak Court Suicide: Source of Poison Not Found|date=2018-11-02|website=Balkan Insight|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPraljak married [[Ka\u0107u\u0161a Babi\u0107]], the former wife of his close friend and poet [[Goran Babi\u0107]]. The couple had no children, but Praljak was close to his stepchildren, Nata\u0161a and Nikola, the latter adding the last name Praljak to his birth name.<ref name=\"Jutarnji\" /><ref name=\"Jutarnji17\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Joint criminal enterprise]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://slobodanpraljak.com/ Personal website]\n* [https://www.slobodanpraljak.com/bibliografija.html Bibliography]\n* [http://www.icty.org/x/cases/prlic/cis/en/cis_prlic_al_en.pdf Prli\u0107 et al.: Case information sheet] at ICTY\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042905/http://hrfilm.hr/baza_redatelj.php?id=73 Profile] at filmski-programi.hr {{in lang|hr}}\n* {{IMDb name|0695182|Slobodan Praljak}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Praljak, Slobodan}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century criminals]]\n[[Category:Academy of Dramatic Art, University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Criminals who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Croatian Defence Council]]\n[[Category:Croatian army officers]]\n[[Category:Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Croatian military personnel who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Croatian people convicted of war crimes]]\n[[Category:Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina convicted of crimes against humanity]]\n[[Category:Faculty of Electrical Engineering and Computing, University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences, University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Filmed suicides]]\n[[Category:People convicted by the International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:People from \u010capljina]]\n[[Category:People who committed suicide in prison custody]]\n[[Category:Suicides by cyanide poisoning]]\n[[Category:Suicides in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina convicted of war crimes]]\n[[Category:Croatian war crimes in the Bosnian War]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Slobodan Praljak\n| image         = Slobodan Praljak.jpg\n| caption       = Praljak in 2017\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1945|01|02|df=y}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2017|11|29|1945|01|02|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[\u010capljina]], [[Independent State of Croatia]]\n| death_place   = [[The Hague]], [[Netherlands]]\n| module        = {{Infobox person|child=yes|death_cause=[[Suicide by poisoning]]}}\n| allegiance    = {{flag|Croatia}}<br />\n| branch        = [[Croatian Army]]<br />[[Croatian Defence Council]]\n| serviceyears  = 1991\u20131995\n| rank          = [[General]]\n| servicenumber =\n| unit          =\n| commands      =\n| battles       = {{plainlist |\n* [[Croatian War of Independence]]\n* [[Bosnian War]]\n* [[Croat\u2013Bosniak War]] }}\n| battles_label =\n| awards        =\n| relations     = \n| spouse        = Ka\u0107u\u0161a Babi\u0107\n| laterwork     = Professor, film and theatre director, businessman, writer\n| signature     =\n| website       = \n}}\n\n'''Slobodan Praljak''' ({{IPA-sh|slob\u01d2dan pr\u01ce\u02d0\u028eak|hr}}; 2 January 1945 \u2013 29 November 2017) was a [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Croat]] general who served in the [[Croatian Army]] and the [[Croatian Defence Council]], an army of the [[Croatian Republic of Herzeg-Bosnia]], between 1992 and 1995. Praljak was found guilty of committing violations of the [[laws of war]], [[crimes against humanity]] and breaches of the [[Geneva Conventions]] during the [[Croat\u2013Bosniak War]] by the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]] (ICTY) in 2017.<ref name=\"ICTY2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/x/cases/prlic/acjug/en/171129-judgement-summary.pdf|title=Trial Judgement Summary for Prli\u0107 et al.|date=29 November 2017|publisher=ICTY|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nPraljak voluntarily joined the newly formed [[Croatian Armed Forces]] after the outbreak of the [[Croatian War of Independence]] in 1991. Before and after the war he was an engineer, a television and theatre director, as well as a businessman.<ref name=\"Ve\u010dernji\">{{cite news|author=Ivica Rado\u0161|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/slobodan-praljak-presuda-haag-sarajevo-general-1210985|title=Tko je bio Slobodan Praljak? Slao je oru\u017eje Bo\u0161njacima u opkoljeno Sarajevo|trans-title=Who was Slobodan Praljak? He sent weapons to Bosnians in the besieged Sarajevo|date=29 November 2017|publisher=[[Ve\u010dernji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Rferl\">{{cite news|author=Andrey Shary|author-link=Andrey Shary|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/commentary-the-poisoned-general-slobodan-praljak-icty/28888298.html|title=The Poisoned General|date=30 November 2017|publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref> Praljak was indicted by, and voluntarily surrendered to, the ICTY in 2004.<ref name=\"TrialIn\">{{cite web|url=https://trialinternational.org/latest-post/slobodan-praljak/|title=Slobodan Praljak|date=6 May 2016|publisher=Trial International|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> In 2013, he was convicted for [[war crime]]s against the [[Bosniak]] population during the Croat\u2013Bosniak War alongside five other Bosnian Croat officials,<ref name=\"ICTY\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/x/cases/prlic/ind/en/prl-ii040304e.htm|title=Prlic et al. Initial Indictment|date=2 March 2004|publisher=ICTY}}</ref><ref name=\"LAT\">{{cite news|url=http://beta.latimes.com/world/la-fg-croatia-slobadan-praljak-20171129-story.html|title='I am not a war criminal,' convicted Bosnian Croat cries as he takes a fatal dose of poison|date=29 November 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=29 November 2017|quote=Ironically, Praljak, who surrendered to the tribunal in April 2004 and had already been jailed for 13 years, could have soon walked free because those who are convicted are generally released after serving two-thirds of their sentences.}}</ref> and was sentenced to 20 years in jail (minus the time he had already spent in detention).<ref>{{cite news|author=Mike Corder|url=http://www.news1130.com/2013/05/29/un-war-crimes-tribunal-convicts-6-bosnian-croats-of-persecution-of-muslims-during-bosnian-war/|title=UN war crimes tribunal convicts 6 Bosnian Croats of persecution of Muslims during Bosnian war|date=29 May 2013|publisher=News1130}}</ref> Upon hearing the guilty verdict upheld in November 2017, Praljak stated that he rejected the verdict of the court, and committed [[suicide by poisoning]] in the courtroom.<ref name=\"icty-statement\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/en/press/statement-on-passing-of-slobodan-praljak|title=Statement on passing of Slobodan Praljak|date=29 November 2017|publisher=ICTY|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"om.nl\">{{cite web|url=https://www.om.nl/@101281/preliminary-results/|title=Preliminary results autopsy Slobodan Praljak|publisher=[[Openbaar Ministerie]]|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|author=Owen Bowcott|title=Bosnian Croat war criminal dies after taking poison in UN courtroom|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2017/nov/29/un-war-crimes-defendant-claims-to-drink-poison-at-trial-in-hague-slobodan-praljak|date=29 November 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|author1=Stephanie van den Berg|author2=Bart H. Meijer|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-warcrimes-bosnia/bosnian-croat-war-crimes-convict-dies-after-taking-poison-in-u-n-court-idUKKBN1DT1E1|title=Bosnian Croat war crimes convict dies after taking 'poison' in U.N. court|date=29 November 2017|agency=Reuters|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and career ==\nSlobodan Praljak was born on 2 January 1945 in [[\u010capljina]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]. His father Mirko worked for the security agency [[OZNA]].<ref name=\"Ve\u010dernji\"/> \n\nPraljak attended high school in [[Li\u0161tica]] with the future Croatian Defense Minister [[Gojko \u0160u\u0161ak]]. He had three university degrees. In 1970, he graduated as an [[electrical engineer]] at the [[Faculty of Electrical Engineering in Zagreb]] with a [[GPA]] of 4.5/5. In 1971, he graduated from the [[Zagreb Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences]], majoring in philosophy and sociology. In 1972, he graduated from the [[Zagreb Academy of Dramatic Art]].<ref name=\"Jutarnji\"/><ref name=\"SDalmacija\"/>\n\nAt first, Praljak worked as a professor and manager of the electronics laboratory at the Nikola Tesla Vocational High School in Zagreb, then lectured on philosophy and sociology,<ref name=\"Jutarnji\">{{cite news|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/tko-je-bio-slobodan-praljak-imao-je-tri-diplome-kontroverzan-ratni-put-ali-i-nevjerojatnu-obiteljsku-pricu-sa-suprugom-i-velikim-prijateljem/6795618/|title=Tko je bio Slobodan Praljak: Imao je tri diplome, kontroverzan ratni put, ali i nevjerojatnu obiteljsku pri\u010du sa suprugom i velikim prijateljem...|trans-title=Who was Slobodan Praljak: He had three diplomas, a controversial war trail, and an incredible family story with his wife and great friend...|date=29 November 2017|publisher=[[Jutarnji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref> and after 1973 was a freelance artist.<ref name=\"SDalmacija\">{{cite news|url=https://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/novosti/hrvatska/clanak/id/519404/tko-je-bio-general-praljak-imao-je-tri-diplome-bio-je-i-slobodni-umjetnik-a-91-dragovoljno-odlazi-na-ratiste-privatni-zivot-obiljezila-mu-je-nevjerojatna-prica|title=Tko je bio general Praljak? Imao je tri diplome, bio je i 'slobodni umjetnik', a '91. dragovoljno odlazi na rati\u0161te; Privatni \u017eivot obilje\u017eila mu je nevjerojatna pri\u010da|trans-title=Who was General Praljak? He had three diplomas, he was also a 'free artist', and '91. he voluntarily goes to the battlefield; His private life marked an incredible story|date=29 November 2017|work=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> Praljak was also a theatre director in theatres in Zagreb, [[Osijek]] and [[Mostar]]. He directed the television series ''Blesan i Tulipan'' [Blesan and Tulipan], television dramas ''Novela od Stanca'' and ''Sarga\u0161ko more'' [Sargasso Sea], documentaries ''Smrt psa'' (1980) [Death of a Dog], ''Sand\u017eak'' and ''Duhan'' [Tobacco] (both in 1990), and film ''Povratak Katarine Ko\u017eul'' (1989) [Return of Katarina Ko\u017eul].<ref name=\"Ve\u010dernji\" /><ref name=\"Jutarnji\"/><ref name=\"Index\">{{cite news|author=Oriana Ivkovi\u0107 Novokmet|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/tko-je-bio-slobodan-praljak-osudjeni-ratni-zlocinac-koji-je-zaradio-milijune-nakon-rata/1010602.aspx|title=Tko je bio Slobodan Praljak? Osu\u0111eni ratni zlo\u010dinac koji je zaradio milijune nakon rata|trans-title=Who was Slobodan Praljak? A guilty war criminal who has earned millions after the war|date=29 November 2017|publisher=[[Index.hr]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Military activity during the Croatian War of Independence and Croat\u2013Bosniak War ==\nPraljak drew public attention in September 1991 when he voluntarily joined the newly formed [[Armed Forces of the Republic of Croatia|Croatian Armed Forces]] after the outbreak of the [[Croatian War of Independence]]. He formed a unit composed of the Zagreb artists and intellectuals with whom he held positions in [[Sunja, Sisak-Moslavina County|Sunja]].<ref name=\"Jutarnji\" /> After the [[Vance plan#Implementation Agreement|Sarajevo Agreement]], by 3 April 1992, he was made [[major general]],<ref name=\"TrialIn\"/> received a number of responsibilities in the [[Ministry of Defence (Croatia)|Ministry of Defence]], and became one of the 14 members of the Croatian National Defence Council and a member of the Croatian State Commission for Relations with [[United Nations Protection Force]] (UNPROFOR). He was the High Representative of the Ministry of Defence, and since 13 May 1993, representative of the Ministry of Defence in the [[Croatian Republic of Herzeg-Bosnia]] and [[Croatian Defence Council]] (HVO).<ref name=\"Jutarnji\" /> Praljak petitioned [[Alija Izetbegovi\u0107]] to unblock [[Sarajevo]] but his propositions were rejected. From 24 July to 8 November 1993, Praljak was the Chief of Staff of the Croatian Defence Council. In spite of the Croat-Muslim conflict in the [[Croat\u2013Bosniak War]], he sent a truck full of weapons to [[Siege of Sarajevo|besieged Sarajevo]] to help Bosniaks. He also allowed the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|UNHCR]]'s humanitarian convoy through to [[Mostar]], which was stopped in [[\u010citluk]].<ref name=\"Ve\u010dernji\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/x/cases/prlic/custom5/en/110331a.pdf|title=Slobodan Praljak's Redacted Final Trial Brief|date=31 March 2011|publisher=ICTY|pages=42\u201343, 86, 177\u2013178}}</ref>\n\nPraljak was accused of failing to prevent the armed forces from committing many crimes of which he was informed and that he could foresee, including removing and placing in detention the Muslim population of [[Prozor, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Prozor]] from July through August 1993, murders in Mostar municipality, the destruction of buildings in East Mostar (including the mosques and the [[Stari Most]]), attacking and wounding of members of international organisations, the destruction and looting of property in [[Gornji Vakuf]] in January 1993, Ra\u0161tani in August 1993, and [[Stupni Do]] in October 1993.<ref name=\"Sheet17\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/x/cases/prlic/cis/en/cis_prlic_al_en.pdf|title=Case Information Sheet: Prli\u0107 et al.|publisher=ICTY|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> During 1993, General Praljak was in charge of the [[Dretelj camp]] where Bosniak men were brutalized, starved, and some killed.<ref name=\"Vulliamy\">{{cite news|last1=Vulliamy|first1=Ed||author-link=Ed Vulliamy|title=The day I came face to face with General Slobodan Praljak in The Hague|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2017/nov/29/the-day-i-came-face-to-face-with-general-slobodan-praljak-in-the-hague|date=29 November 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> \n\nPraljak was accused of ordering the destruction of Mostar's [[Stari Most]] in November 1993, an act which [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia|ICTY]] ruled had \"caused disproportionate damage to the Muslim civilian population\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/un-war-crimes-court-yugoslavia-final-verdict/28885760.html|title=War Criminal Dies After 'Taking Poison' In Hague Courtroom|date=29 November 2017|publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|access-date=30 November 2017}}</ref> However, ICTY agreed that the bridge was a legitimate military target.<ref name=\"Guardian\" /> During the trial, Praljak denied the accusation because in the same month when the destruction occurred, he came into conflict with the commander of the HVO's so-called ''Punishment Battalion'' [[Mladen Naletili\u0107 Tuta]] which resulted in his resignation from the positions of HVO's Chief of Staff, one day before the destruction of the bridge. He said that the bridge was demolished by activation of the explosive charge set on the left bank of the [[Neretva]], where the [[Army of the Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Army of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] was located.<ref name=\"Jutarnji\" /><ref>{{cite news|author=Gordana Knezevi\u0107|author-link=Gordana Knezevi\u0107|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/balkans-without-borders-mostar-bridge-praljiak/28884107.html|title=The Cultured Destroyers of Culture|date=29 November 2017|publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> In addition to the responsibility and whether it was a legitimate military target, ICTY also examined whether the earlier siege by [[Yugoslav People's Army|JNA]] and Bosnian Serb forces contributed to the bridge's collapse.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f2KrCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA315|title=Bosnia and the Destruction of Cultural Heritage|publisher=Routledge|author=Helen Walasek, contributions by Richard Carlton, Amra Had\u017eimuhamedovi\u0107, Valery Perry, Tina Wik|page=315|isbn=9781317172994|date=2016-03-03}}</ref> Praljak retired from military service at his own request on 1 December 1995.<ref name=\"SDalmacija\"/>\n\n== Postwar career ==\nAfter the war, Praljak became a businessman.<ref name=\"SDalmacija\"/> In 1995, Praljak co-founded a company with his brother Zoran called Oktavijan. His company initially produced films, video, and television programs and published Praljak\u2019s books. It later engaged in real estate business by managing a business complex ''Centar 2000'' in Zagreb. Since 2005, the company is owned and managed by his stepson Nikola Babi\u0107 Praljak.<ref name=\"Jutarnji17\">{{cite news|author=Tomislav Kukec|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/najneobicnija-obiteljska-prica-s-ovih-prostora-haaskom-sudu-duguje-tri-milijuna-eura-a-u-zagrebu-gradi-velebni-centar-od-14-milijuna-eura/5816487/|title=Najneobi\u010dnija Pri\u010da S Ovih Prostora: Haa\u0161kom sudu duguje tri milijuna eura, a u Zagrebu gradi velebni centar od 14 milijuna eura|trans-title=Most unusual story from the region: Owes three million euros to the Hague Tribunal, and in Zagreb is building a big center worth 14 million euros|date=26 March 2017|work=[[Jutarnji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> In 2011 it had around 22 million [[Croatian kuna|kunas]] of revenue.<ref name=\"Jutarnji2012\">{{cite news|author=Kre\u0161imir \u017dabec|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/ministarstvo-generalu-praljku-vase-knjige-o-ratu-spadaju-u-sund-i-pornografiju-platit-cete-628.726-kuna-poreza/1537959/|title=Ministarstvo generalu Praljku: Va\u0161e knjige o ratu spadaju u \u0161und i pornografiju, platit \u0107ete 628.726 kuna poreza!|date=4 July 2012|publisher=[[Jutarnji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> Praljak was also a co-owner of Liberan, a company that has a share in [[Ljubu\u0161ki]] Tobacco Factory,<ref name=\"Index\" /> and owned other shares in few other companies.<ref name=\"Jutarnji17\" /> In 2008, the [[Ministry of Culture (Croatia)|Croatian Ministry of Culture]] deemed that 18 of his works about the Croatian War of Independence, Bosnian War, and relations between Croatia and Bosnia and Herzegovina were not books but brochures of worthless literature,<ref name=\"Jutarnji2012\"/> and in 2013 the [[Ministry of Finance (Croatia)|Ministry of Finance]] made an enforcement charge of 435 thousand kunas.<ref name=\"Sata\">{{cite new|url=https://www.24sata.hr/news/tko-je-slobodan-praljak-bio-u-tri-vojske-i-zavrsio-tri-fakulteta-550352|title=Tko je Slobodan Praljak? Bio u tri vojske i zavr\u0161io tri fakulteta|trans-title=Who was Slobodan Praljak? He was in three armies and finished three faculties|date=29 November 2017|work=[[24sata (Croatia)|24sata]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref> In total, he authored 25 works.<ref name=\"Jutarnji17\"/> Since 2012, The Hague Tribunal's secretariat requested Praljak to recover defence costs of around EUR 2.8-3.3 million, as they estimated that he had assets and shares worth EUR 6.5 million which allowed him to fund the costs of his defence. Praljak and his lawyer refused the estimation statement because he had no property in his name even from the beginning of the trial.<ref name=\"Sata\"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Vanja Nezirovi\u0107|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/luksuzno-carstvo-generala-praljak-svu-imovinu-prebacio-na-sina-i-tvrdi-da-nema-bas-nista/1554003/|title=Luksuzno Carstvo Generala: Praljak svu imovinu prebacio na sina i tvrdi da nema ba\u0161 ni\u0161ta!|trans-title=Luxury Empire of General: Praljak all assets transferred to his son and says that he has nothing!|date=31 August 2012|work=[[Jutarnji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/neobicni-zahtjeva-s-haaskog-suda-mozete-li-nam-pomoci-locirati-imovinu-generala-praljka-duzan-nam-je-28-milijuna-eura/5800395/|title=Neobi\u010dni Zahtjev S Ha\u0161kog Suda: 'Mo\u017eete li nam pomo\u0107i locirati imovinu generala Praljka... du\u017ean nam je 2,8 milijuna eura!'|trans-title=An Unusual Request from the Hague Tribunal: \"Can you help us locate the property of General Praljak ... he owes us 2.8 million euros!\"|date=22 March 2017|work=[[Jutarnji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== ICTY indictment ==\nPraljak was among six accused by the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]] (ICTY), in relation to the [[Croatian Republic of Herzeg-Bosnia]].<ref name=\"ICTY\" /> On 5 April 2004, he voluntarily surrendered and was transferred to the ICTY.<ref name=\"TrialIn\"/> In his indictment it was alleged that Praljak as a senior military official commanded, directly and indirectly, the Herceg-Bosna/HVO armed forces which committed mass war crimes against Bosnian Muslim population in 8 municipalities in Bosnia and Herzegovina during a [[joint criminal enterprise]] between 1992 and 1994. In his role as a high-ranking official in the Ministry of Defence, he was closely involved in all aspects of not only the Herceg-Bosna/HVO military planning and operations but the actions of the Herceg-Bosna/HVO civilian police too.<ref name=\"ICTY\" /> On 6 April, he appeared before ICTY and pleaded not guilty.<ref name=\"TrialIn\"/> He chose to defend himself without a lawyer.<ref name=\"Vulliamy\"/>\n\nThe indictment charged on the basis of their individual and superior criminal responsibility, but subsequently in judgment only on the basis of individual criminal responsibility. Praljak was found guilty on (taken from the UN press release 2004, 2017):\n{{quote|\n* four counts of grave breaches of the [[Geneva Conventions]] (willful killing; unlawful deportation, transfer and confinement of a civilian; inhuman treatment; extensive destruction of property and appropriation of property, not justified by military necessity and carried out unlawfully and wantonly).\n* six counts of violations of the [[Law of war|laws or customs of war]] (cruel treatment; unlawful labour; destruction or wilful damage done to institutions dedicated to religion or education; plunder of public or private property; unlawful attack on civilians; unlawful infliction of terror on civilians)\n* five counts of [[crimes against humanity]] (persecutions on political, racial and religious grounds; murder; deportation; imprisonment; inhumane acts)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/en/press/jadranko-prlic-bruno-stojic-slobodan-praljak-milivoj-petkovic-valentin-coric-and-berislav-0|title=Press Release: Jadranko Prlic, Bruno Stojic, Slobodan Praljak, Milivoj Petkovic, Valentin Coric and Berislav Pusic|date=6 April 2004|publisher=ICTY|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Sheet17\"/>}}\n\nThe trial began on 26 April 2006. On 29 May 2013 the Trial Chamber judgement sentenced him to 20 years of imprisonment (the sentence took into account the time he had already spent in detention), and on 28 June 2013, Praljak filed an appeal.<ref name=\"TrialIn\"/> On 29 November 2017, the ICTY trial was concluded finding him guilty, and although some parts of his conviction were overturned, the judge did not reduce the initial sentence of 20 years.<ref name=\"ICTY2017\"/><ref name=\"Guardian\" /><ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|author=Marlise Simons|author-link=Marlise Simons|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/29/world/europe/bosnian-war-croatia.html|title=Croatian War Criminal Dies After Swallowing Poison in Court|date=29 November 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref> He was charged with crimes against \"humanity, violations of the laws or customs of war, and grave breaches of the Geneva Conventions\", also \"extensive appropriation of property not justified by military necessity\" and \"plunder of public or private property through the third category of joint criminal enterprise liability\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/en/press/the-icty-renders-its-final-judgement-in-the-prli%C4%87-et-al-appeal-case|title=The ICTY renders its final judgement in the Prli\u0107 et al. appeal case|date=29 November 2017|publisher=ICTY|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> on which given his [[command responsibility]] he failed to act and prevent.<ref name=\"Rferl\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Praljak: Police investigate Hague trial suicide|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42177772|date=30 November 2017|publisher=BBC|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> He was acquitted of some charges related to the destruction of [[Stari Most]].<ref name=\"Rferl\"/><ref name=\"LAT\" /> As he had already served more than two-thirds of the sentence in jail (around 13 years and several months), he would probably have been released soon.<ref name=\"LAT\" /><ref>{{cite news|author=Davor Ivankovi\u0107|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/slobodan-praljak-haag-sloboda-kazna-otrov-1210894|title=Da nije popio otrov, Praljak bi uskoro bio na slobodi|trans-title=If he did not drank the poison, Praljak would soon be at liberty|date=29 November 2017|publisher=[[Ve\u010dernji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nOn 29 November 2017, during the pronouncement of the appeal judgment against him, Praljak addressed the judges, saying: \"Judges, Slobodan Praljak is not a war criminal. With disdain, I reject your verdict!\"<ref name=\"HRT\">{{cite news|url=http://vijesti.hrt.hr/417745/sudac-agius-ovo-je-bio-vrlo-dug-i-slozen-postupak|title=Na izricanju presude Slobodan Praljak popio otrov i preminuo|trans-title=At the pronouncement of the verdict Slobodan Praljak drank the poison and passed away|date=29 November 2017|publisher=[[Croatian Radiotelevision]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Post\">{{cite news|author=Willa Frej|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/slobodan-praljak-dies-poison_us_5a1ebb4fe4b0cb0e917cfe4b?ncid=inblnkushpmg00000009|title=Former Bosnian Croat Official on Trial For War Crimes Dies After Drinking Poison in Court|date=29 November 2017|work=HuffPost|access-date=1 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"aljaz\">{{cite news|title=Slobodan Praljak umro u bolnici|trans-title=Slobodan Praljak died in hospital|url=http://balkans.aljazeera.net/vijesti/slobodan-praljak-umro-u-bolnici|work=Al Jazeera Balkans|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=1 December 2017|language=Serbo-Croatian}}</ref> He then drank what he said was poison,<ref name=\"HRT\" /><ref name=\"Post\" /> leading presiding judge Carmel Agius to suspend the hearings.<ref name=\"Reuters\" /> ICTY medical staff transported Praljak to nearby HMC Hospital,<ref name=\"icty-statement\" /> where he died.<ref name=\"LAT\" /><ref name=\"om.nl\"/> The Dutch authorities declared the courtroom a crime scene and launched an investigation.<ref name=\"Reuters\" /><ref name=\"icty-statement\"/> His body was cremated in Zagreb in a private ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/report-croat-war-criminal-cremated-after-death-at-hague/2017/12/09/818660ec-dcdf-11e7-a241-0848315642d0_story.html?tid=hybrid_collaborative_1_na|title=Report: Croat war criminal cremated after death at Hague|date=9 December 2017|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Reaction ===\nFormer ICTY judges [[Wolfgang Schomburg]] and [[Richard Goldstone]] commented that \"it is a tragedy that someone in such a situation has taken their own life\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Zoran Arbutina|url=http://www.dw.com/en/icty-hague-tribunal-ends-prosecutions-of-yugoslav-war-crimes-but-legacy-lingers/a-41587892|title=ICTY Hague Tribunal ends prosecutions of Yugoslav war crimes but legacy lingers|date=29 November 2017|publisher=Deutsche Welle|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> Goldstone added: \"In a way, the victims are deprived of this deed. They did not get full justice.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nacional.hr/goldstone-praljak-je-uskratio-pravdu-zrtvama/|title=Goldstone: 'Praljak je uskratio pravdu \u017ertvama'|trans-title=Goldstone: 'Praljak has denied justice to the victims'|date=1 December 2017|publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref> [[Martin Bell]] described Praljak as a \"theatrical character\" who \"died in a theatrical way\".<ref name=\"Sky\">{{cite news|author=Alan McGuinness|title=War criminal Slobodan Praljak dies after taking poison in court|url=https://news.sky.com/story/war-criminal-slobodan-praljak-dies-after-taking-poison-in-court-11148960|date=29 November 2017|publisher=Sky News|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref> [[Andrey Shary]] for [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] noted that \"Praljak's [[Seppuku|samurai final act]] might evoke respect or sympathy\", but \"individual perceptions of honor don't always coincide with correctness\".<ref name=\"Rferl\"/> \n\nWriting in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', journalist Harry de Quetteville opined that the defiant suicide was \"the most dramatic proof possible of a very uncomfortable reality: many in the Balkans refuse to accept that the horrific ethnic cleansing of the 1990s was wrong\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=de Quetteville|first1=Harry|title=Balkans suicide: the poison is not just in court but across the whole region|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/29/balkans-suicide-poison-not-just-court-across-whole-region/|accessdate=30 November 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=29 November 2017}}</ref> Former [[United States Ambassador-at-Large for War Crimes Issues|US Ambassador for War Crimes Issues]] [[Stephen Rapp]] compared Praljak's suicide by poisoning to that of another war crimes convict, [[Hermann G\u00f6ring]], noting that in both cases the verdict nevertheless \"stands for all history in establishing the facts and in showing that the perpetrators of atrocities will be held to account\".<ref name=\"Biddle\">{{cite news|last=Biddle|first=Jo|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20171201-un-court-closes-under-cloud-war-criminals-suicide|title=UN court closes under cloud of Slobodan Praljak's suicide|date=1 December 2017|work=Agence France Presse|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Regional reaction ====\nThe [[Croatian government]] offered condolences to Praljak's family and said the ICTY misrepresented its officials in the 1990s. Prime Minister [[Andrej Plenkovi\u0107]] stated that Praljak's suicide illustrated the \"deep moral injustice towards the six Croats from Bosnia and Herzegovina and the Croatian people\".<ref>{{cite web|title=PM: Praljak's act speaks of deep moral injustice towards Bosnian Croats|url=https://vlada.gov.hr/news/pm-praljak-s-act-speaks-of-deep-moral-injustice-towards-bosnian-croats/22949|date=29 November 2017|publisher=[[Government of Croatia]]|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref> All the party caucuses of the [[Croatian Parliament]] except the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia|SDP]] and [[Civic Liberal Alliance|GLAS]] issued a joint statement declaring that ICTY's verdict did not respect the \"historical truths, facts and evidence\", and that it was \"unjust and unacceptable\", adding that Praljak symbolically warned of all the verdicts' injustice with his suicide. They expressed their condolences to the families of victims of crimes committed during the [[Bosnian War]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://vijesti.hrt.hr/417952/jandrokovic-procitao-zajednicku-izjavu-presude-ne-uvazavaju-povijesne-istine |title=Jandrokovi\u0107 pro\u010ditao zajedni\u010dku izjavu: Presude ne uva\u017eavaju povijesne istine |trans-title=Jandrokovi\u0107 read a joint statement: The judgments do not respect the historical truths |date=30 November 2017 |publisher=Croatian Radiotelevision |language=Serbo-Croatian |accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> Croatian president [[Kolinda Grabar-Kitarovi\u0107]] expressed her condolences to Praljak's family, calling him \"a man who preferred to die rather than live as a convict for crimes he did not commit\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://vijesti.hrt.hr/417929/obracanje-javnosti-predsjednice-rh-u-povodu-presude-haskog-suda|title=Predsjednica: Hrvatski narod prvi se odupro velikosrpskoj agresiji brane\u0107i svoju opstojnost i opstojnost BiH|trans-title=President: The Croatian people first resisted the Greater Serbia aggression by defending its survival and the survival of BiH|date=30 November 2017|publisher=Croatian Radiotelevision|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> [[Miroslav Tu\u0111man]] stated it was a \"consequence of his moral position not to accept the verdict that has nothing to do with justice or reality\".<ref name=\"Sky\" />\n\nThe [[List of Bosniak members of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosniak member]] of the [[Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Bakir Izetbegovi\u0107]], said that Praljak was led to suicide by the joint criminal enterprise,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/izetbegovic-praljka-je-upropastio-projekt-udruzenog-zlocinackog-pothvata-foto-20171129|title=Izetbegovi\u0107: Praljka je upropastio projekt udru\u017eenog zlo\u010dina\u010dkog pothvata|trans-title=Izetbegovi\u0107: Praljak was ruined by the project of a joint criminal enterprise|date=29 November 2017|publisher=Tportal.hr|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> while Croat [[Chairman of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Chairman]] [[Dragan \u010covi\u0107]] stated that Praljak had sacrificed his life to prove his innocence.<ref name=\"LAT\" /> Serbian President [[Aleksandar Vu\u010di\u0107]] said he would not mock Praljak's suicide but has criticized the reaction of Croatian officials, stating that it would have been unacceptable for him to praise a convicted war criminal as a hero or to denounce an ICTY verdict.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.b92.net/info/vesti/index.php?yyyy=2017&mm=11&dd=30&nav_category=64&nav_id=1330955|title=Vu\u010di\u0107 o Praljku: Ne bih se rugao i nazivao kukavi\u010dkim|trans-title=Vucic about Praljak: I would not mock and called it cowardly|date=30 November 2017|publisher=[[B92]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> The Serbian politician [[Vojislav \u0160e\u0161elj]] commented that, although he was an enemy, it was a \"heroic move worthy of respect\" and there should have been more such strong blows to the tribunal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espreso.rs/vesti/hronika/202957/junacki-cin-za-postovanje-seselj-za-espreso-komentarise-samoubistvo-hrvatskog-generala-usred-haskog-tribunala-video?ref=ext_kurir|title=Juna\u010dki \u010din za po\u0161tovanje! \u0160e\u0161elj za Espreso komentari\u0161e samoubistvo hrvatskog generala usred Ha\u0161kog tribunala|trans-title=Heroic move for respect! \u0160e\u0161elj for Espreso comments suicide of Croatian general in the middle of Hague tribunal|date=29 November 2017|work=Espreso.rs|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> \n\nAlmost a thousand Bosnian Croats gathered in the Mostar and \u010capljina squares to [[candlelight vigil|light candles]] to pay respect to Praljak.<ref name=\"LAT\" /><ref>{{cite news|author=Andrew MacDowall|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/02/slobodan-praljak-suicide-reopens-old-wounds-bosnia|title=Slobodan Praljak's suicide reopens old wounds in Bosnia|date=2 December 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> On December 11, 2017, a commemoration for Slobodan Praljak was held in Zagreb. The event was attended by two thousand people, including Government ministers [[Damir Krsti\u010devi\u0107]] and Tomo Medved (as private citizens), a number of MPs, mostly from the [[Croatian Democratic Union]] party, and some retired army officers that participated in the 1990s war. In the evening, a religious ceremony was also held at a Catholic church. During the same day, members of the [[Youth Initiative for Human Rights]] made a commemoration for the victims of Croatian forces urging condemnation of that period policies.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sven Milekic|url=https://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/zagreb-commemorates-praljak-by-rejecting-verdict-12-11-2017|title=War Criminal Praljak\u2019s Death Commemorated in Croatia|date=11 December 2017|work=Balkan Insight|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Darko Bandic|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/croat-nationalists-honor-general-convicted-of-war-crimes/2017/12/11/32bf4970-de6e-11e7-b2e9-8c636f076c76_story.html|title=Croat nationalists honor general convicted of war crimes|date=11 December 2017|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nPresident Grabar-Kitarovi\u0107 has been pressured to take away wartime decorations from Praljak and other convicted officials, but she refused to do so stating that they received it for defence against Serbian aggression, adding that \"such practice has not been implemented so far, except in the case of verdicts made by the Croatian courts\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/tihomir-blaskic-dario-kordic-odlikovanja-1213585|title=Odlikovanja RH nisu oduzeta ni Tihomiru Bla\u0161ki\u0107u, Dariju Kordi\u0107u...|trans-title=The Republic of Croatia decorations have not been taken away either from Tihomir Bla\u0161ki\u0107, Darijo Kordic...|date=12 December 2017|publisher=[[Ve\u010dernji list]]|language=Serbo-Croatian|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Investigation ===\n{{update section|date=November 2018}}\nA preliminary [[autopsy]] determined that Praljak had [[cyanide poisoning|poisoned]] himself with [[potassium cyanide]], which caused his heart to fail.<ref name=\"om.nl\" /> How the poison was obtained and brought into the courtroom is to be the subject of an official investigation.<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite news|author=Mike Corder|url=http://time.com/5044356/slobodan-praljak-war-crimes-poison/|title=The Container That Croat War Criminal Praljak Drank From Held a Deadly Chemical, Prosecutor Says|date=1 December 2017|work=Time|accessdate=1 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031537/http://time.com/5044356/slobodan-praljak-war-crimes-poison/|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Praljak's lawyer Nika Pinter suggested that he may have committed suicide because he could not accept being convicted as a war criminal and that the act had been long-planned.<ref>{{cite news|author=Darko Bandic|url=https://www.apnews.com/26667453debf458f92b6ea8a7e5bc799/Lawyer:--Convicted-Croat-general-might-have-planned-death|title=Lawyer: Convicted Croat general might have planned death|date=5 December 2017|work=Associated Press|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> \n\nThe cyanide that Praljak took was not listed as a prohibited substance under Dutch law.\n\n\u201cWith regards to the investigation concerning assistance in the commission of suicide, the Dutch authorities conducted a thorough investigation of how Praljak could get a hold of the cyanide. Witnesses were interviewed, video materials watched, rooms in which Praljak stayed were checked and numerous materials inspected. However, no information was found concerning the question on how Praljak came into possession of that substance,\u201d the prosecutors\u2019 report said. The report added that video surveillance recordings did not show if Praljak carried the vial of poison with him or if it was handed to him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://balkaninsight.com/2018/11/02/slobodan-praljak-court-suicide-source-of-poison-unclear-11-02-2018/|title=Slobodan Praljak Court Suicide: Source of Poison Not Found|date=2018-11-02|website=Balkan Insight|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPraljak married [[Ka\u0107u\u0161a Babi\u0107]], the former wife of his close friend and poet [[Goran Babi\u0107]]. The couple had no children, but Praljak was close to his stepchildren, Nata\u0161a and Nikola, the latter adding the last name Praljak to his birth name.<ref name=\"Jutarnji\" /><ref name=\"Jutarnji17\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Joint criminal enterprise]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://slobodanpraljak.com/ Personal website]\n* [https://www.slobodanpraljak.com/bibliografija.html Bibliography]\n* [http://www.icty.org/x/cases/prlic/cis/en/cis_prlic_al_en.pdf Prli\u0107 et al.: Case information sheet] at ICTY\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042905/http://hrfilm.hr/baza_redatelj.php?id=73 Profile] at filmski-programi.hr {{in lang|hr}}\n* {{IMDb name|0695182|Slobodan Praljak}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Praljak, Slobodan}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century criminals]]\n[[Category:Academy of Dramatic Art, University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Criminals who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Croatian Defence Council]]\n[[Category:Croatian army officers]]\n[[Category:Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Croatian military personnel who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Croatian people convicted of war crimes]]\n[[Category:Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina convicted of crimes against humanity]]\n[[Category:Faculty of Electrical Engineering and Computing, University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences, University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Filmed suicides]]\n[[Category:People convicted by the International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:People from \u010capljina]]\n[[Category:People who committed suicide in prison custody]]\n[[Category:Suicides by cyanide poisoning]]\n[[Category:Suicides in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina convicted of war crimes]]\n[[Category:Croatian war crimes in the Bosnian War]]\n", "name_user": "Opencooper", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInvestigation:one word", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slobodan_Praljak"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mississippi", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Mississippi, United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mississippi\n| map1 =\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| legend1 =\n{{legend|#a5130f|Confirmed cases}}\n| location = [[Mississippi]], U.S\n| first_case = [[Forrest County, Mississippi|Forrest County]]\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| arrival_date = March 12, 2020<ref name=\"first\">{{Cite Web|date=12 March 2020|access-date=12 March 2020|title=First Case of Coronavirus in Mississippi|url=https://www.deltanews.tv/news/first-case-of-coronavirus-in-mississippi/article_75c2dea4-6467-11ea-ad25-13433a2a000a.html}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases= 1,455\n| recovery_cases = \n| deaths = 35\n<!--As of April 3, 2020-->\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| website = [https://msdh.ms.gov/msdhsite/_static/14,0,420.html Mississippi State Department of Health]\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Mississippi]] in March 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Mississippi medical cases chart}}\n\nThe [[Mississippi State Department of Health]] (MSDH) confirmed their first case in the state on March 12, 2020. The individual is from [[Forrest County, Mississippi|Forrest County]], who had recently traveled to the state of Florida.<ref name=\"first\"/> Three days later, on March 15, the state had a spike in cases (4) in the state bringing the total to 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcbi.com/10-coronavirus-cases-reported-mississippi/|title=10 CORONAVIRUS CASES REPORTED IN MISSISSIPPI|last=Matlock|first=Cash|date=March 15, 2020|website=WCBI-TV|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, two new cases in the state, one in [[Pearl River County, Mississippi|Pearl River County]] and another [[Monroe County, Mississippi|Monroe County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wxxv25.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-two-cases-covid-19-pearl-river-county-one-hancock-county/|title=CORONAVIRUS: TWO CASES OF COVID-19 IN PEARL RIVER COUNTY, ONE IN HANCOCK COUNTY|last=Keiek|first=Brantly|date=March 16, 2020|website=WXXV-TV|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\nOn March 17, cases in the state jumped from 12 to 21, with 4 in [[Hinds County, Mississippi|Hinds County]], 3 in [[Leflore County, Mississippi|Leflore County]], one in [[Jackson County, Mississippi|Jackson County]], and one in [[Harrison County, Mississippi|Harrison County]]. The next day, on March 18, cases spiked up to 34, with [[DeSoto County, Mississippi|DeSoto County]] seeing their first case, along with [[Madison County, Mississippi|Madison County]] and [[Perry County, Mississippi|Perry County]]. [[Bolivar County, Mississippi|Bolivar County]] saw their first 2 cases. The following day, on March 19, the state saw 16 cases and its first death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wlbt.com/2020/03/19/health-department-confirms-mississippis-first-coronavirus-death/|title=HEALTH DEPARTMENT CONFIRMS MISSISSIPPI'S FIRST CORONAVIRUS DEATH|last=Lee|first=China|date=March 19, 2020|website=wlbt.tv|language=en|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\nHarris and Pearl River counties saw 3 new cases each, while the counties of DeSoto, Forrest, and Jackson counties saw one additional case, while at least one new case were reported in the counties of Holmes, Jones, Smith, Walthall, Wilkinson, Winston, and Yazoo. On March 20, the state saw 30 new cases, bringing the total up to 80. New cases were reported in Adams, Franklin, Humphreys, Lawrence, Lee, Marshall, Monroe, Pike, Rankin, Tippah, and Webster counties, while additional cases were reported in Coahoma, DeSoto, Hancock, Harrison, Hinds, Holmes, Jackson, and Madison counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmcactionnews5.com/2020/03/13/cases-coronavirus-identified-by-miss-dept-health/|title=CASES CORONAVIRUS IDENTIFIED BY MISS DEPT HEALTH|author=WLBT.com Staff|date=March 13, 2020|website=wmcactionnews5|language=en|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\nOn March 21, the state jumped in cases, reporting 60 new cases, jumping the total to 140.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.djournal.com/news/state-news/mississippi-coronavirus-cases-up-to/article_c20d021d-ab00-5a75-81b5-a174857bb61c.html/|title=MISSISSIPPI CORONAVIRUS CASES UP TO 140|last=Burnett|first=Jayson|date=March 21, 2020|website=djournal|language=en|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\nMarch 22 saw 67 new cases in the state, with most counties in the state ending up with a new case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/coronavirus-cases-increase-to-207-in-mississippi/ar-BB11xEFv/|title=CORONAVIRUS CASES INCREASE TO 207 IN MISSISSIPPI|last=Fowler|first=Sarah|date=March 22, 2020|website=MSN News|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government responses==\nOn March 14, two days after the first case was announced in the state, Governor [[Tate Reeves]], declared a state of emergency, due to how big of an impact the neighboring state of Louisiana, has had with the virus. Louisiana at the time was the most infected state per capita.<ref name=\"DSE\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/2020/03/14/mississippi-coronavirus-gov-reeves-declares-state-emergency/5050744002/|title=Mississippi declares state of emergency over coronavirus as Louisiana hard hit|last=Broom|first=Brian|date=March 14, 2020|website=Clarion Ledger|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Reeves recently came back from a trip from Spain (a country hit hard by the virus) and stated that he will voluntarily work from home for precautionary purposes.<ref name=\"DSE\"/>\n\nMarch 15, [[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]]'s city mayor [[Chokwe Antar Lumumba]] declared civil emergency for the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wlbt.com/2020/03/16/jackson-mayor-declare-civil-emergency-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Jackson mayor to declare civil emergency amid coronavirus outbreak|last=Lee|first=China|date=March 15, 2020|website=WLBT|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, the mayor of [[Tupelo, Mississippi|Tupelo]], [[Jason Shelton]], imposed a [[stay-at-home order]] that went into effect early on March 22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtva.com/content/news/Tupelo--569001971.html/|title=Tupelo now under stay-at-home order to prevent coronavirus spread|author=Sydney Darden/Craig Ford|date=March 21, 2020|website=WVTA|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same day, [[Columbus, Mississippi|Columbus]] put in a curfew from 10 pm to 6 am until further notice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtva.com/content/news/columbus-curfew-568998021.html/|title=Columbus implements curfew and restrictions on businesses, other gatherings|last=Carlisle|first=Zac|date=March 21, 2020|website=WVTA|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Governor Reeves issued an executive order deeming most businesses as \"essential\" including restaurants, bars and other establishments including dining in but limiting to 10 persons.  The order also banned local governments from imposing stricter orders.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gov. Tate Reeves Signs New Executive Order in Response to COVID-19 Spread |url=https://www.jacksonfreepress.com/news/2020/mar/24/gov-tate-reeves-signs-new-executive-order-slow-spr/ |website=Jackson Free Press |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> However, the wording of the executive order lead to some confusion among local governments on the authority of the state overriding that of restrictions put into place by municipalities and counties.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ganusheau |first1=Adam |title=Mayors scramble to know: Does Gov. Reeves\u2019 coronavirus declaration clash with local orders? |url=https://www.sunherald.com/news/politics-government/article241524861.html |website=Biloxi Sun Herald |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In response to criticism and confusion expressed by the public and local officials, Governor Reeves issued a supplemental order on March 26 that clarified that stricter restrictions put into place by local governing bodies were allowed.<ref> web |last1=Cook |first1=Cathy |title=Clarifications on conflicting executive orders |url=https://www.picayuneitem.com/2020/03/local-business-restrictions-to-prevent-the-spread-of-covid-19-remain-in-place/ |website=Picayune Item |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, an additional executive order was issued by the Governor, announcing a state-wide shelter-in-place order, requiring all non-essential businesses to close and overrides previous allowances for dine-in services in restaurants made in the March 24 executive order.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ladd |first1=Donna |last2=Judin |first2=Nick |title=Governor Does About-Face, Issues Statewide \u2018Shelter In Place\u2019 For Mississippi |url=https://www.jacksonfreepress.com/news/2020/apr/01/governor-does-about-face-issues-statewide-shelter-/ |website=Jackson Free Press |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\nOn March 12, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |COVID-19 cases in Mississippi\nas of April 3, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed <br> cases\n!Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Adams County, Mississippi|Adams]]\n|16\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Alcorn County, Mississippi|Alcorn]]\n|6\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Amite County, Mississippi|Amite]]\n|6\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Attala County, Mississippi|Attala]]\n|14\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Benton County, Mississippi|Benton]]\n|5\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bolivar County, Mississippi|Bolivar]]\n|34\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Calhoun County, Mississippi|Calhoun]]\n|4\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Carroll County, Mississippi|Carroll]]\n|5\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Chickasaw County, Mississippi|Chickasaw]]\n|15\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Choctaw County, Mississippi|Choctaw]]\n|8\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Claiborne County, Mississippi|Claiborne]]\n|1\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Clarke County, Mississippi|Clarke]]\n|5\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Clay County, Mississippi|Clay]]\n|7\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Coahoma County, Mississippi|Coahoma]]\n|27\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Copiah County, Mississippi|Copiah]]\n|12\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Covington County, Mississippi|Covington]]\n|4\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Desoto County, Mississippi|Desoto]]\n|118\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Forrest County, Mississippi|Forrest]]\n|34\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Franklin County, Mississippi|Franklin]]\n|4\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[George County, Mississippi|George]]\n|4\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Grenada County, Mississippi|Grenada]]\n|