World Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]] || United States ([[Oklahoma]]) || TUL || [[Tulsa International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Medford, Oregon|Medford]] || United States ([[Oregon]]) || MFR || [[Rogue Valley International\u2013Medford Airport]] ||\n|-\n|[[Erie, Pennsylvania|Erie]] || United States ([[Pennsylvania]]) || ERI || [[Erie International Airport]] ||\n|-\n| [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]] || United States ([[Rhode Island]]) || PVD || [[T. F. Green Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Greenville, South Carolina|Greenville]]/[[Spartanburg, South Carolina|Spartanburg]] || United States ([[South Carolina]]) || GSP || [[Greenville\u2013Spartanburg International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]] || United States ([[South Dakota]]) || RAP || [[Rapid City Regional Airport]] ||\n|-\n| [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota|Sioux Falls]] || United States ([[South Dakota]]) || FSD || [[Sioux Falls Regional Airport]] ||\n|-\n| [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] || United States ([[Tennessee]]) || TYS || [[McGhee Tyson Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] || United States ([[Tennessee]]) || MEM || [[Memphis International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Amarillo, Texas|Amarillo]] || United States ([[Texas]]) || AMA || [[Rick Husband Amarillo International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]] || United States ([[Texas]]) || ELP || [[El Paso International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Lubbock, Texas|Lubbock]] || United States ([[Texas]]) || LBB || [[Lubbock Preston Smith International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Midland, Texas|Midland]] || United States ([[Texas]]) || MAF || [[Midland International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Roanoke, Virginia|Roanoke]] || United States ([[Virginia]]) || ROA || [[Roanoke Regional Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]] || United States ([[Wisconsin]]) || MSN || [[Dane County Regional Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin|Milwaukee]] || United States ([[Wisconsin]]) || MKE || [[Milwaukee Mitchell International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Casper, Wyoming|Casper]] || United States ([[Wyoming]]) || CPR || [[Casper\u2013Natrona County International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Cody, Wyoming|Cody]] || United States ([[Wyoming]]) || COD || [[Yellowstone Regional Airport]] ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==Fleet==\nPrior to its shutdown, the Trans States Airlines fleet consisted of the following aircraft:\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse\"\n|+ '''Trans State Airlines Fleet'''\n|-\n!Aircraft\n!In service\n!Passengers\n!Operated For\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Embraer ERJ-145]]\n|align=center|45<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.planespotters.net/airline/Trans-States-Airlines|title=Trans States Airlines Fleet Details and History|website=www.planespotters.net|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|align=center|50\n|align=center|[[United Express]]\n|Most to transfer to [[ExpressJet]]\n|-\n!Total\t\n!45\n!colspan=3|\n|}\n</center>\n\nIn October 2009, Trans States Holdings announced an agreement to purchase 50 Mitsubishi MRJ90 with options for 50 more.<ref name=\"MRJ90\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.transstates.net/Mitsubishi_PR10.02.09.pdf|title=Trans States Holdings Signs LOI with Mitsubishi Aircraft for Purchase of 100 MRJ Aircraft|publisher=transstates.net|date=2009-10-02 |accessdate=2013-06-01}}</ref> Trans States Holdings held conversion rights to take the smaller, 76-seat MRJ70 instead of the 92-seat MRJ90 dependent on the scope clause environment by the time the airline took delivery.<ref name=\"MRJ90Firm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/ain-news-live/regional-airline-association-convention/2013-05-07/mitsubishi-specifies-certification-schedule-mrj/ |title=Mitsubishi Specifies Certification Schedule for MRJ |publisher=AIN Online|date=2013-05-07 |accessdate=2013-06-01}}</ref> The order was cancelled as of October 2019 due to concerns that the [[Mitsubishi SpaceJet]] M90 aircraft violates the US [[Scope clause]] laws.<ref>https://www.aviation24.be/forums/viewtopic.php?f=7&t=51067&start=51</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, Trans States Airlines began taking delivery of six former [[Passaredo Linhas A\u00e9reas]] ERJ-145s.<ref name=\"USAirwaysCease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.ch/portal/news/18419-trans-states-airlines-takes-on-six-ex-passaredo-erj-145s |title=Trans States Airlines takes on six ex-Passaredo ERJ-145s |publisher=CH Aviation|date=2013-04-26 |accessdate=2013-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Trans States began parking their United Express ERJ-145ER's, in exchange for ERJ-145XR's transferred from ExpressJet Airlines.\n\n==Previously operated turboprop aircraft==\n\nPrior to becoming an all-jet airline, Trans States operated several different turboprop aircraft types including:\n\n* [[ATR 42]]\n* [[ATR 72]]\n* [[British Aerospace]] [[BAe Jetstream 31]] \n* [[British Aerospace]] [[BAe Jetstream 41]]\n* [[Embraer EMB-120 Brasilia]] \n* [[Fairchild Swearingen Metro III]]\n\nThese propjet aircraft were operated in [[code share]] feeder services for [[American Airlines]], [[Delta Air Lines]], [[Trans World Airlines]] ([[TWA]]), [[USAir]] and [[US Airways]].<ref>http://www.airliners.net, photos of Trans States Airlines aircraft</ref>\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n*July 14, 2004\n**Trans States Airlines Flight 3504, operated and marketed as a US Airways Express flight, overran the runway at [[Ottawa Macdonald-Cartier International Airport]] and sustained damage to the left inboard tire. There were no serious injuries. [http://www.tsb.gc.ca/eng/rapports-reports/aviation/2004/a04o0188/a04o0188.pdf Transport Safety Board of Canada Accident Report]\n*June 16, 2010\n**Trans States Airlines Flight 8050, operated and marketed as a United Express flight, overran the runway at [[Ottawa Macdonald-Cartier International Airport]] and sustained damage to the front of the aircraft with a nose gear collapse. Both pilots and one passenger sustained minor injuries.<ref name=AH42d059bc>{{cite web|url=http://avherald.com/h?article=42d059bc&opt=0 |title=Accident: Trans States E145 at Ottawa on Jun 16th 2010, runway overrun |first=Simon |last=Hradecky |publisher=Aviation Herald |accessdate=17 June 2010}}</ref>\n* March 1, 2011 at 6:45 am EST\n** A [[US Airways]] Embraer 145 operated by Trans States Airlines was being pushed back from the gate at [[Bradley International Airport]] for a departure to [[Pittsburgh International Airport|Pittsburgh]] when the front nose gear collapsed and the front of the plane dropped to the tarmac. None of the 29 passengers were injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courant.com/community/windsor-locks/hc-windsor-locks-plane-emergency0302-20110301,0,6384155.story|title=Plane Emergency At Bradley|work=tribunedigital-thecourant}}</ref>\n*September 4, 2011\n**Trans States Airlines Flight 3363 originating from Chicago IL, operated as a United Express flight, left the runway during landing at [[Ottawa Macdonald-Cartier International Airport]]. The aircraft, with 44 passengers on board, sustained damage to the main gear and belly, as well as to the right wing. There were no injuries to passengers or crew.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ottawa.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20110904/OTT_plane_runway_110904/20110904/?hub=OttawaHome|title=No injuries after plane slides off Ottawa runway|work=Ottawa}}</ref>\n*February 22, 2012\n**Trans States Airlines operating as United Express Flight 3350 originating from Chicago O'Hare, IL to Rochester, NY was on approach to land but overran the end of the runway by about 50\u201375 feet and came to a stop with all gear off the paved surface. There were no injuries. The passengers disembarked via mobile stairs and were bussed to the terminal.\n*August 7, 2018\n**A Trans States Airlines [[Embraer 145]] operating as Flight 4697 from Washington Dulles to Providence, RI was forced to divert to John F. Kennedy International Airport after reports of smoke in the cabin. The aircraft was evacuated on the runway. Three of the 53 passengers received treatment at the scene.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|United States|Companies|Aviation}}\n* [http://www.transstates.net/ Trans States Airlines]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Airlines of the United States}}\n{{Delta Connection Carriers}}\n{{United Express Carriers}}\n{{American Eagle Carriers}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct regional airlines of the United States]]\n[[Category:Airlines established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Airlines disestablished in 2020]]\n[[Category:Regional Airline Association members]]\n[[Category:Companies based in St. Louis County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Former Oneworld affiliate members]]\n[[Category:Defunct airlines of the United States]]\n[[Category:1985 establishments in Missouri]]\n[[Category:2020 disestablishments in Missouri]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox airline\n| airline = Trans States Airlines\n| image = \n| logo = Trans States Airlines (TSA - Trans States).png\n| logo_size = 150\n| fleet_size = 0\n| destinations = 70\n| IATA = AX\n| ICAO = LOF\n| callsign = WATERSKI\n| parent = [[Trans States Holdings|Trans States Holdings, Inc.]]\n| founded = 1982 (as Resort Air)\n| defunct = April 1 2020\n| num_employees = \n| headquarters = [[Bridgeton, Missouri|Bridgeton]], [[Missouri]]\n| key_people = Hulas Kanodia (Chairman)<br>Richard A. Leach<br>(President)<br>Fred Oxley<br>(COO)\n| aoc = RAIA379A<ref name=\"FAA\">{{Cite web|url=https://av-info.faa.gov/detail.asp?DSGN_CODE=RAIA&OPER_FAR=121&OPER_NAME=TRANS+STATES+AIRLINES+LLC|title=Federal Aviation Administration - Airline Certificate Information - Detail View|website=av-info.faa.gov|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref>\n| hubs = '''As [[United Express]]:'''\n*[[O'Hare International Airport|Chicago-O'Hare International Airport]]\n*[[Denver International Airport]]|\n| focus_cities = \n| frequent_flyer = [[Mileage Plus]]<br>(United Express)\n| alliance = [[Star Alliance]] (United Express)\n| website = {{url|transstates.net}}\n}}\n\n'''Trans States Airlines''' was a regional airline owned by [[Trans States Holdings]] and headquartered in [[Bridgeton, Missouri]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transstates.net/corporate.html |title=Trans States Airlines :: Corporate Information |publisher=transstates.net |date= |accessdate=2012-10-05}} \"Executive Offices Trans States Airlines 11495 Navaid Rd. Suite 340 Bridgeton, Missouri 63044\"</ref>\n\nAt the time of its closing, the airline operated flights for [[United Airlines]] under the [[United Express]] brand. Trans States Airlines ceased all operations on April 1, 2020.<ref name=\"stlpd\">{{cite web |author1=Jacob Barker |title=Regional carrier Trans States Airlines to stop flying April 1 as airlines reel from coronavirus |url=https://www.stltoday.com/business/local/regional-carrier-trans-states-airlines-to-stop-flying-april-as/article_584da247-4105-506b-8494-3446a7c32265.html |website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |publisher=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe company began operations as '''Resort Air''' in 1982.<ref name=\"tsahistory\">[http://www.transstates.net/history.html TSA History] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124132946/http://www.transstates.net/history.html |date=2010-11-24 }} November 12, 2009</ref> As an independent commuter air carrier, Resort Air operated [[Swearingen Metro]] propjets from a small hub located in [[St. Louis]] (STL) with service to [[Carbondale, Illinois]]; [[Columbia, Missouri]]; [[Fort Leonard Wood, MO]]; [[Joplin, MO]]; [[Lake of the Ozarks]], MO; [[Springfield, IL]]; and [[Springfield, MO]].<ref>http://www.departedflights.com, May 1, 1984 Resort Air route map</ref> In 1985, the company entered into an agreement with [[Trans World Airlines]] ([[TWA]]) to operate as [[Trans World Express]] serving six cities in Missouri and Illinois.\n\nResort Air changed its name to Trans States Airlines in 1989. That same year, TSA began operations on the west coast as [[USAir Express]] at [[Los Angeles]] (LAX) and by 1995 was serving [[Fresno]], [[Monterey]], [[Ontario, CA]], [[Palm Springs]], [[San Diego]], [[San Luis Obispo]] and [[Santa Barbara County, California|Santa Barbara]] nonstop from LAX with [[British Aerospace]] [[BAe Jetstream 31]] propjets.<ref>http://www.departedflights.com, April 2, 1995 Official Airline Guide (OAG), Los Angeles flight schedules for USAir Express</ref> By 1999, Trans States was operating BAe Jetstream 31 flights from LAX as [[US Airways Express]] nonstop to just four destinations in California:  Fresno, Palm Springs, San Diego and Santa Barbara.<ref>http://www.departedflights.com, June 1, 1999 Official Airline Guide (OAG), Los Angeles flight schedules</ref>\n\nOn the east coast, in 1995, TSA began operations as a [[code share]] feeder airline into [[New York City]] [[JFK Airport]] as United Express.<ref name=\"tsahistory\"/> By 1999, Trans States had begun operations as a [[Delta Connection]] [[code share]] air carrier for [[Delta Air Lines]] at New York JFK Airport with [[Embraer ERJ-145]] regional jets and [[British Aerospace]] [[BAe Jetstream 41]] propjets with nonstop service to [[Albany, NY]], [[Baltimore]], [[Greensboro, NC]], [[Hartford]]/[[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]], [[Norfolk, VA]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Pittsburgh]], [[Raleigh]]/[[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], [[Richmond, VA]] and [[Rochester, NY]].<ref>http://www.departedflights.com, June 1, 1999 Official Airline Guide (OAG), New York JFK flight schedules</ref>\n\nThe call sign \"Waterski\" and the ICAO 3-letter identifier \"LOF,\" which stands for ''''L'''odge '''o'''f the '''F'''our Seasons', are from the early days when the company was operated as Resort Air and took visitors to the [[Lake of the Ozarks]] in Missouri.\n\nIn 2015, the airline carried 3.6 million passengers.<ref name=\"tsaabout\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transstates.net/about.html|title=Trans States Airlines :: About Our Airline|publisher=transstates.net|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728190131/http://www.transstates.net/about.html|archivedate=2012-07-28|accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref> \n\nIn February 2020, the airline announced their intent to gradually cease operations through 2020 and transfer their fleet to [[ExpressJet|ExpressJet Airlines]] per an agreement with [[United Airlines]]. However, on March 17, 2020, CEO Rick Leach sent a memo to employees stating that due to the impact of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] on travel demand, the airline would cease operations on April 1, 2020, much earlier than originally expected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forums.jetcareers.com/attachments/img_20200317_121755_707-jpg.51885/|title=Memo from Rick Leach to Trans States Airlines employees|last=|first=|date=March 17, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"stlpd\" /> [[Compass Airlines (North America)|Compass Airlines]], another regional airline owned by Trans States Holdings, also announced a cessation of operations effective April 7, 2020, leaving [[GoJet Airlines]] as the only operating airline owned by Trans States Holdings. \n\nThe final Trans States Airlines flight was [[United Express]] Flight 4695 from [[Springfield\u2013Branson National Airport|Springfield, Missouri]] to [[Denver International Airport|Denver, Colorado]] on April 1, 2020.\n\n== St. Louis TWA Express Hub Operations in 1990 ==\n\nTrans States was operating 48-passenger [[ATR-42]] and 19-passenger [[Fairchild Swearingen Metroliner]] (Metro III model) propjets in [[Trans World Express]] [[code share]] service for [[Trans World Airlines]] at this time from the TWA hub in St. Louis with nonstop flights to the following destinations:<ref>http://www.departedflights.com, 1990 Trans States Airlines/Trans World Express route map</ref>\n\n* [[Burlington, IA]]\n* [[Chicago, IL]] ([[Meigs Field]]) - ''one stop service via Springfield, IL''\n* [[Columbia, MO]]\n* [[Des Moines, IA]]\n* [[Joplin, MO]]\n* [[Lincoln, NE]]\n* [[Madison, WI]]\n* [[Memphis, TN]]\n* [[Moline, IL]]\n* [[Peoria, IL]]\n* [[Sioux City, IA]]\n* [[Springfield, IL]]\n* [[Springfield, MO]]\n\n== St. Louis TWA Express Hub Operations in 1995 ==\n\nBy 1995, Trans States had expanded its [[Trans World Express]] [[code sharing]] operations at the TWA St. Louis hub and was operating [[ATR-42]], [[ATR-72]], [[British Aerospace]] [[BAe Jetstream 31]] and [[BAe Jetstream 41]], and [[Embraer EMB-120 Brasilia]] turboprops with nonstop flights to the following destinations:<ref>http://www.departedflights.com, April 2, 1995 Official Airline Guide (OAG), St. Louis flight schedules</ref>\n\n* [[Birmingham, AL]]\n* [[Bloomington, IL]]\n* [[Burlington, IA]]\n* [[Cape Girardeau, MO]]\n* [[Cedar Rapids, IA]]\n* [[Champaign, IL]]\n* [[Chicago, IL]] ([[Midway Airport]])\n* [[Columbia, MO]]\n* [[Decatur, IL]]\n* [[Des Moines, IA]]\n* [[Evansville, IN]]\n* [[Fayetteville, AR]]\n* [[Fort Wayne, IN]]\n* [[Grand Rapids, MI]]\n* [[Joplin, MO]]\n* [[Lexington, KY]]\n* [[Knoxville, TN]]\n* [[Madison, WI]]\n* [[Marion, IL]]\n* [[Memphis, TN]]\n* [[Milwaukee, WI]]\n* [[Moline, IL]]\n* [[Paducah, KY]]\n* [[Peoria, IL]]\n* [[Quincy, IL]]\n* [[Sioux City, IA]]\n* [[South Bend, IN]]\n* [[Springfield, IL]]\n* [[Springfield, MO]]\n* [[Waterloo, IA]]\n\n==Destinations==\n[[File:TSA ERJ145 N803HK.jpg|right|thumb|An ERJ 145EP at Washington Dulles International Airport]]\nPrior to its shutdown, the airline operated to the following destinations under the [[United Express]] brand:<ref name=\"Route Map\">{{cite web|title=Route Map|url=http://www.transstates.net/Documents/March19%20AX%20Map.png|website=www.transstates.net|accessdate=May 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+\n|-\n! City !! Country (Subdivision) !! IATA !! Airport !! Notes\n|-\n| [[Montreal|Montr\u00e9al]] || Canada ([[Quebec]]) || YUL || [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Trudeau Int