o Falls Regional Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Chicago]] || United States ([[Illinois]]) || ORD || [[O'Hare International Airport]] || {{Airline hub}}\n|-\n| [[Moline, Illinois|Moline]] || United States ([[Illinois]]) || MLI || [[Quad City International Airport]] ||\n|-\n| [[Peoria, Illinois|Peoria]] || United States ([[Illinois]]) || PIA || [[General Wayne A. Downing Peoria International Airport]] ||\n|-\n| [[Evansville, Indiana|Evansville]] || United States ([[Indiana]]) || EVV || [[Evansville Regional Airport]] ||\n|-\n| [[South Bend, Indiana|South Bend]] || United States ([[Indiana]]) || SBN || [[South Bend International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]] || United States ([[Iowa]]) || DSM || [[Des Moines International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]] || United States ([[Kansas]]) || ICT || [[Wichita Mid-Continent Airport|Wichita Eisenhower National Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] || United States ([[Missouri]]) || MCI || [[Kansas City International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]] || United States ([[Kentucky]]) || SDF || [[Louisville International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Detroit]] || United States ([[Michigan]]) || DTW || [[Detroit Metropolitan Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]] || United States ([[Michigan]]) || GRR || [[Gerald R. Ford International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Lansing, Michigan|Lansing]] || United States ([[Michigan]]) || LAN || [[Capital Region International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Traverse City, Michigan|Traverse City]] || United States ([[Michigan]]) || TVC || [[Cherry Capital Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] || United States ([[Missouri]]) || STL || [[St. Louis Lambert International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Springfield, Missouri|Springfield]] || United States ([[Missouri]]) || SGF || [[Springfield\u2013Branson National Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Billings, Montana|Billings]] || United States ([[Montana]]) || BIL || [[Billings Logan International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Great Falls, Montana|Great Falls]] || United States ([[Montana]]) || GTF || [[Great Falls International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Helena, Montana|Helena]] || United States ([[Montana]]) || HLN || [[Helena Regional Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Kalispell, Montana|Kalispell]] || United States ([[Montana]]) || FCA || [[Glacier Park International Airport]] || FAA LID code is GPI\n|-\n| [[Missoula, Montana|Missoula]] || United States ([[Montana]]) || MSO || [[Missoula International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln]] || United States ([[Nebraska]]) || LNK || [[Lincoln Airport (Nebraska)|Lincoln Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]] || United States ([[Nebraska]]) || OMA || [[Eppley Airfield]] || \n|-\n| [[Albuquerque, New Mexico|Albuquerque]] || United States ([[New Mexico]]) || ABQ || [[Albuquerque International Sunport]] || \n|-\n| [[Santa Fe, New Mexico|Santa Fe]] || United States ([[New Mexico]]) || SAF || [[Santa Fe Regional Airport]] ||  \n|-\n| [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] || United States ([[New York (state)|New York]]) || BUF || [[Buffalo Niagara International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]] || United States ([[New York (state)|New York]]) || ROC || [[Greater Rochester International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Greensboro, North Carolina|Greensboro]] || United States ([[North Carolina]]) || GSO || [[Piedmont Triad International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]]/[[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]] || United States ([[North Carolina]]) || RDU || [[Raleigh\u2013Durham International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Bismarck, North Dakota|Bismarck]] || United States ([[North Dakota]]) || BIS || [[Bismarck Municipal Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Dickinson, North Dakota|Dickinson]] || United States ([[North Dakota]]) || DIK || [[Dickinson Theodore Roosevelt Regional Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Fargo, North Dakota|Fargo]] || United States ([[North Dakota]]) || FAR || [[Hector International Airport]] ||\n|-\n| [[Minot, North Dakota|Minot]] || United States ([[North Dakota]]) || MOT || [[Minot International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Williston, North Dakota|Williston]] || United States ([[North Dakota]]) || ISN || [[Sloulin Field International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Akron, Ohio|Akron]]/[[Canton, Ohio|Canton]] || United States ([[Ohio]]) || CAK || [[Akron\u2013Canton Regional Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]] || United States ([[Ohio]]) || CLE || [[Hopkins International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]] || United States ([[Ohio]]) || CMH || [[John Glenn Columbus International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]] || United States ([[Ohio]]) || DAY || [[Dayton International Airport]] ||\n|-\n| [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma|Oklahoma City]] || United States ([[Oklahoma]]) || OKC || [[Will Rogers World Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]] || United States ([[Oklahoma]]) || TUL || [[Tulsa International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Medford, Oregon|Medford]] || United States ([[Oregon]]) || MFR || [[Rogue Valley International\u2013Medford Airport]] ||\n|-\n|[[Erie, Pennsylvania|Erie]] || United States ([[Pennsylvania]]) || ERI || [[Erie International Airport]] ||\n|-\n| [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]] || United States ([[Rhode Island]]) || PVD || [[T. F. Green Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Greenville, South Carolina|Greenville]]/[[Spartanburg, South Carolina|Spartanburg]] || United States ([[South Carolina]]) || GSP || [[Greenville\u2013Spartanburg International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]] || United States ([[South Dakota]]) || RAP || [[Rapid City Regional Airport]] ||\n|-\n| [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota|Sioux Falls]] || United States ([[South Dakota]]) || FSD || [[Sioux Falls Regional Airport]] ||\n|-\n| [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] || United States ([[Tennessee]]) || TYS || [[McGhee Tyson Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] || United States ([[Tennessee]]) || MEM || [[Memphis International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Amarillo, Texas|Amarillo]] || United States ([[Texas]]) || AMA || [[Rick Husband Amarillo International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]] || United States ([[Texas]]) || ELP || [[El Paso International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Lubbock, Texas|Lubbock]] || United States ([[Texas]]) || LBB || [[Lubbock Preston Smith International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Midland, Texas|Midland]] || United States ([[Texas]]) || MAF || [[Midland International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Roanoke, Virginia|Roanoke]] || United States ([[Virginia]]) || ROA || [[Roanoke Regional Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]] || United States ([[Wisconsin]]) || MSN || [[Dane County Regional Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin|Milwaukee]] || United States ([[Wisconsin]]) || MKE || [[Milwaukee Mitchell International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Casper, Wyoming|Casper]] || United States ([[Wyoming]]) || CPR || [[Casper\u2013Natrona County International Airport]] || \n|-\n| [[Cody, Wyoming|Cody]] || United States ([[Wyoming]]) || COD || [[Yellowstone Regional Airport]] ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==Fleet==\nPrior to its shutdown, the Trans States Airlines fleet consisted of the following aircraft:\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse\"\n|+ '''Trans State Airlines Fleet'''\n|-\n!Aircraft\n!In service\n!Passengers\n!Operated For\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Embraer ERJ-145]]\n|align=center|45<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.planespotters.net/airline/Trans-States-Airlines|title=Trans States Airlines Fleet Details and History|website=www.planespotters.net|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|align=center|50\n|align=center|[[United Express]]\n|Most to transfer to [[ExpressJet]]\n|-\n!Total\t\n!45\n!colspan=3|\n|}\n</center>\n\nIn October 2009, Trans States Holdings announced an agreement to purchase 50 Mitsubishi MRJ90 with options for 50 more.<ref name=\"MRJ90\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.transstates.net/Mitsubishi_PR10.02.09.pdf|title=Trans States Holdings Signs LOI with Mitsubishi Aircraft for Purchase of 100 MRJ Aircraft|publisher=transstates.net|date=2009-10-02 |accessdate=2013-06-01}}</ref> Trans States Holdings held conversion rights to take the smaller, 76-seat MRJ70 instead of the 92-seat MRJ90 dependent on the scope clause environment by the time the airline took delivery.<ref name=\"MRJ90Firm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/ain-news-live/regional-airline-association-convention/2013-05-07/mitsubishi-specifies-certification-schedule-mrj/ |title=Mitsubishi Specifies Certification Schedule for MRJ |publisher=AIN Online|date=2013-05-07 |accessdate=2013-06-01}}</ref> The order was cancelled as of October 2019 due to concerns that the [[Mitsubishi SpaceJet]] M90 aircraft violates the US [[Scope clause]] laws.<ref>https://www.aviation24.be/forums/viewtopic.php?f=7&t=51067&start=51</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, Trans States Airlines began taking delivery of six former [[Passaredo Linhas A\u00e9reas]] ERJ-145s.<ref name=\"USAirwaysCease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.ch/portal/news/18419-trans-states-airlines-takes-on-six-ex-passaredo-erj-145s |title=Trans States Airlines takes on six ex-Passaredo ERJ-145s |publisher=CH Aviation|date=2013-04-26 |accessdate=2013-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Trans States began parking their United Express ERJ-145ER's, in exchange for ERJ-145XR's transferred from ExpressJet Airlines.\n\n==Previously operated turboprop aircraft==\n\nPrior to becoming an all-jet airline, Trans States operated several different turboprop aircraft types including:\n\n* [[ATR 42]]\n* [[ATR 72]]\n* [[British Aerospace]] [[BAe Jetstream 31]] \n* [[British Aerospace]] [[BAe Jetstream 41]]\n* [[Embraer EMB-120 Brasilia]] \n* [[Fairchild Swearingen Metro III]]\n\nThese propjet aircraft were operated in [[code share]] feeder services for [[American Airlines]], [[Delta Air Lines]], [[Trans World Airlines]] ([[TWA]]), [[USAir]] and [[US Airways]].<ref>http://www.airliners.net, photos of Trans States Airlines aircraft</ref>\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n*July 14, 2004\n**Trans States Airlines Flight 3504, operated and marketed as a US Airways Express flight, overran the runway at [[Ottawa Macdonald-Cartier International Airport]] and sustained damage to the left inboard tire. There were no serious injuries. [http://www.tsb.gc.ca/eng/rapports-reports/aviation/2004/a04o0188/a04o0188.pdf Transport Safety Board of Canada Accident Report]\n*June 16, 2010\n**Trans States Airlines Flight 8050, operated and marketed as a United Express flight, overran the runway at [[Ottawa Macdonald-Cartier International Airport]] and sustained damage to the front of the aircraft with a nose gear collapse. Both pilots and one passenger sustained minor injuries.<ref name=AH42d059bc>{{cite web|url=http://avherald.com/h?article=42d059bc&opt=0 |title=Accident: Trans States E145 at Ottawa on Jun 16th 2010, runway overrun |first=Simon |last=Hradecky |publisher=Aviation Herald |accessdate=17 June 2010}}</ref>\n* March 1, 2011 at 6:45 am EST\n** A [[US Airways]] Embraer 145 operated by Trans States Airlines was being pushed back from the gate at [[Bradley International Airport]] for a departure to [[Pittsburgh International Airport|Pittsburgh]] when the front nose gear collapsed and the front of the plane dropped to the tarmac. None of the 29 passengers were injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courant.com/community/windsor-locks/hc-windsor-locks-plane-emergency0302-20110301,0,6384155.story|title=Plane Emergency At Bradley|work=tribunedigital-thecourant}}</ref>\n*September 4, 2011\n**Trans States Airlines Flight 3363 originating from Chicago IL, operated as a United Express flight, left the runway during landing at [[Ottawa Macdonald-Cartier International Airport]]. The aircraft, with 44 passengers on board, sustained damage to the main gear and belly, as well as to the right wing. There were no injuries to passengers or crew.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ottawa.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20110904/OTT_plane_runway_110904/20110904/?hub=OttawaHome|title=No injuries after plane slides off Ottawa runway|work=Ottawa}}</ref>\n*February 22, 2012\n**Trans States Airlines operating as United Express Flight 3350 originating from Chicago O'Hare, IL to Rochester, NY was on approach to land but overran the end of the runway by about 50\u201375 feet and came to a stop with all gear off the paved surface. There were no injuries. The passengers disembarked via mobile stairs and were bussed to the terminal.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|United States|Companies|Aviation}}\n* [http://www.transstates.net/ Trans States Airlines]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Airlines of the United States}}\n{{Delta Connection Carriers}}\n{{United Express Carriers}}\n{{American Eagle Carriers}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct regional airlines of the United States]]\n[[Category:Airlines established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Airlines disestablished in 2020]]\n[[Category:Regional Airline Association members]]\n[[Category:Companies based in St. Louis County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Former Oneworld affiliate members]]\n[[Category:Defunct airlines of the United States]]\n[[Category:1985 establishments in Missouri]]\n[[Category:2020 disestablishments in Missouri]]\n", "name_user": "Justsaph", "label": "safe", "comment": "added flight 4697", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trans_States_Airlines"}
{"title_page": "1977 Cincinnati Bearcats football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1977\n| team = Cincinnati Bearcats\n| conference = Independent\n| division = \n| short_conf = \n| record = 5\u20134\u20132\n| conf_record =\n| head_coach = [[Ralph Staub (American football)|Ralph Staub]]\n| hc_year = 1st\n| off_scheme = \n| def_scheme = \n| captain = Gardner Cobb, Howie Kurnick, Napolean Outlaw, Dan Rains, [[Mike Woods (American football)|Mike Woods]]\n| stadium = [[Nippert Stadium]]\n| champion = \n}}\n{{1977 Division I Independents football records}}\nThe '''1977 Cincinnati Bearcats football team''' represented [[University of Cincinnati]] during [[1977 NCAA Division I-A football season]]. The Bearcats, led by first-year head coach [[Ralph Staub (American football)|Ralph Staub]], participated as [[NCAA Division I FBS independent schools|independent]] and played their home games at [[Nippert Stadium]].\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 1977\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 10\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1977|team=Northwestern State Demons|title=Northwestern State}}\n| site_stadium = [[Nippert Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, OH]]\n| score = 41\u20130\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 17\n| w/l = t\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[1977 Louisville Cardinals football team|Louisville]]\n| site_stadium = [[Old Cardinal Stadium|Cardinal Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Louisville|Louisville, KY]]\n| gamename = [[Keg of Nails]]\n| score = 17\u201317\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 24\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1977|team=Louisiana\u2013Monroe Warhawks|title=Northeast Louisiana}}\n| site_stadium = Nippert Stadium\n| site_cityst = Cincinnati, OH\n| score = 63\u20130\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 1\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1977|team=Southern Miss Golden Eagles|ti